1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,880
Has you ever walked out of a concert feeling like you just ran like a half marathon?

2
00:00:06,220 --> 00:00:08,220
Yeah, that complete physical exhaustion.

3
00:00:08,380 --> 00:00:08,700
Exactly.

4
00:00:08,880 --> 00:00:13,200
Even though you spent the entire two hours just sitting comfortably in a velvet chair.

5
00:00:13,360 --> 00:00:13,680
Right.

6
00:00:13,860 --> 00:00:16,840
Maybe your ears are ringing a bit, sure, but it's more than that.

7
00:00:16,880 --> 00:00:17,460
It really is.

8
00:00:17,760 --> 00:00:23,440
Your muscles feel fatigued, like your chest feels tight, and your core is actually physically

9
00:00:23,440 --> 00:00:24,160
exhausted.

10
00:00:24,260 --> 00:00:25,380
We've all had that feeling.

11
00:00:25,480 --> 00:00:26,300
We really have.

12
00:00:26,300 --> 00:00:31,580
Whether it's walking out of a massive symphony performance or, you know, a thumping rock

13
00:00:31,580 --> 00:00:36,660
show, or even just taking off your headphones after a really intense emotional album.

14
00:00:36,940 --> 00:00:41,780
It is a completely universal experience, and historically we've had a very hard time explaining

15
00:00:41,780 --> 00:00:42,020
it.

16
00:00:42,220 --> 00:00:42,440
Yeah.

17
00:00:42,740 --> 00:00:46,020
We say we are moved by the music, which is, you know, a lovely poetic sentiment.

18
00:00:46,200 --> 00:00:46,540
Oh, totally.

19
00:00:46,720 --> 00:00:52,060
But it doesn't really explain the biology of why your quadriceps are tense after listening

20
00:00:52,060 --> 00:00:52,620
to Beethoven.

21
00:00:52,820 --> 00:00:53,100
Right.

22
00:00:53,100 --> 00:01:00,780
And usually when we talk about human anatomy or physiology, we expect this level of engineering

23
00:01:00,780 --> 00:01:01,380
precision.

24
00:01:01,720 --> 00:01:06,080
If you break your arm, you go to the hospital, they take an x-ray, the doctor points to a

25
00:01:06,080 --> 00:01:09,780
jagged white line on a glowing screen and says, well, there is your problem.

26
00:01:10,040 --> 00:01:10,680
It's visible.

27
00:01:11,140 --> 00:01:11,920
It is measurable.

28
00:01:12,480 --> 00:01:14,080
Biology loves categories.

29
00:01:14,380 --> 00:01:15,080
It really does.

30
00:01:15,100 --> 00:01:18,680
It loves a clear cause and an observable physical effect.

31
00:01:18,680 --> 00:01:23,440
But then you step into the world of music and human emotion, and suddenly that x-ray machine

32
00:01:23,440 --> 00:01:25,140
feels completely useless.

33
00:01:25,420 --> 00:01:26,240
Oh, entirely.

34
00:01:26,620 --> 00:01:31,840
We know definitively that a song can make us cry or make us want to dance or leave us completely

35
00:01:31,840 --> 00:01:32,360
drained.

36
00:01:32,620 --> 00:01:39,500
But if you try to find the mechanism, the actual gears and levers turning inside us, you are

37
00:01:39,500 --> 00:01:42,180
looking at a landscape that is incredibly murky.

38
00:01:42,540 --> 00:01:43,260
It really is.

39
00:01:43,260 --> 00:01:49,140
How does an invisible vibration in the air become like physical exhaustion in your stomach?

40
00:01:49,400 --> 00:01:52,300
That is the absolute definition of diagnostic muddy waters.

41
00:01:52,680 --> 00:01:57,480
But that invisible bridge between acoustic sound waves and the human flesh is exactly what

42
00:01:57,480 --> 00:01:58,660
we are going to cross today.

43
00:01:59,080 --> 00:02:01,060
Welcome to today's Deep Dive.

44
00:02:01,280 --> 00:02:04,880
If you're listening to this right now, our mission is to completely revolutionize how you

45
00:02:04,880 --> 00:02:06,380
experience your favorite playlist.

46
00:02:06,380 --> 00:02:12,580
Whether you are listening to a complex jazz ensemble, a heavy metal anthem, or honestly

47
00:02:12,580 --> 00:02:17,640
just the ambient noise of the subway train outside your window, we are going to change

48
00:02:17,640 --> 00:02:22,040
the way you understand what is happening inside your physical body at this very second.

49
00:02:22,200 --> 00:02:22,440
Yes.

50
00:02:22,880 --> 00:02:27,340
And we are pulling all of this from an incredibly fascinating text by Arnie Cox.

51
00:02:27,500 --> 00:02:27,720
Right.

52
00:02:27,820 --> 00:02:30,440
The book is called Music and Embodied Cognition.

53
00:02:31,120 --> 00:02:33,060
Listening, Moving, Feeling, and Thinking.

54
00:02:33,060 --> 00:02:39,100
And at the center of Cox's work is this concept called the Mimetic Hypothesis.

55
00:02:39,440 --> 00:02:41,100
And I don't use this phrase lightly.

56
00:02:41,440 --> 00:02:45,660
It is a proposition that fundamentally rewrites how we define the act of listening.

57
00:02:45,880 --> 00:02:47,240
Okay, let's unpack this right away.

58
00:02:47,480 --> 00:02:52,140
Because the central idea here is that you, me, and everyone listening, we don't just listen

59
00:02:52,140 --> 00:02:53,100
to music with our ears.

60
00:02:53,180 --> 00:02:53,400
Right.

61
00:02:53,640 --> 00:02:54,840
That's a biological illusion.

62
00:02:55,240 --> 00:03:00,080
The hypothesis suggests that we actually play and sing along with every piece of music we

63
00:03:00,080 --> 00:03:00,380
hear.

64
00:03:00,540 --> 00:03:01,760
Even when we're sitting still.

65
00:03:01,760 --> 00:03:02,320
Exactly.

66
00:03:02,680 --> 00:03:07,740
Using our muscles, our vocal cords, and our motor neurons, even when we are sitting perfectly,

67
00:03:07,880 --> 00:03:08,600
completely still.

68
00:03:09,160 --> 00:03:10,880
You aren't just absorbing sound.

69
00:03:11,120 --> 00:03:13,800
Your body is actively, physically surviving it.

70
00:03:14,040 --> 00:03:19,740
To really grasp how radical this idea is, we have to look at the traditional way humanity

71
00:03:19,740 --> 00:03:20,660
has studied music.

72
00:03:21,040 --> 00:03:24,040
And frankly, the traditional way we've studied the human brain.

73
00:03:24,180 --> 00:03:24,360
Yeah.

74
00:03:24,480 --> 00:03:29,600
For centuries, there has been this massive disconnect between the people who play music and the people

75
00:03:29,600 --> 00:03:30,500
who analyze it.

76
00:03:30,500 --> 00:03:36,920
And Cox kicks off his entire exploration with a story from his grad school days that illustrates

77
00:03:36,920 --> 00:03:38,520
this disconnect perfectly.

78
00:03:38,660 --> 00:03:39,620
It's a great story.

79
00:03:39,780 --> 00:03:42,660
I love this anecdote because it is so incredibly relatable.

80
00:03:43,380 --> 00:03:44,600
So picture this.

81
00:03:45,380 --> 00:03:47,220
Cox is a music theory student.

82
00:03:47,600 --> 00:03:53,160
He is sitting in his apartment, completely buried in the complex structural music theory of the

83
00:03:53,160 --> 00:03:54,800
composer Claude Debussy.

84
00:03:54,800 --> 00:03:55,320
Right.

85
00:03:55,460 --> 00:03:57,320
And Debussy is famously intricate.

86
00:03:57,820 --> 00:03:58,160
Oh, yeah.

87
00:03:58,320 --> 00:04:03,300
We are talking about dense harmonic structures, whole tone scales, very mathematical, highly

88
00:04:03,300 --> 00:04:04,500
cerebral compositions.

89
00:04:04,960 --> 00:04:05,280
Exactly.

90
00:04:05,500 --> 00:04:10,440
So Cox is at his desk mapping out the hierarchical relations among these musical tones, drawing

91
00:04:10,440 --> 00:04:12,640
charts, doing the heavy academic lifting.

92
00:04:12,760 --> 00:04:13,520
Doing the work.

93
00:04:13,640 --> 00:04:15,120
And suddenly his stove breaks.

94
00:04:15,380 --> 00:04:16,660
So he has to call a repairman.

95
00:04:16,660 --> 00:04:23,040
A very grounded, physical, blue-collar problem, interrupting his high-level, abstract, ivory

96
00:04:23,040 --> 00:04:23,920
tower thinking.

97
00:04:24,240 --> 00:04:25,160
Perfect contrast.

98
00:04:25,680 --> 00:04:29,520
So the stove repairman comes over, gets to work, and they start making small talk.

99
00:04:30,300 --> 00:04:34,180
The repairman asks Cox what he is studying up at the college.

100
00:04:34,300 --> 00:04:34,440
Right.

101
00:04:34,680 --> 00:04:36,140
Cox replies, music theory.

102
00:04:36,140 --> 00:04:38,240
And the repairman gets super excited.

103
00:04:38,940 --> 00:04:44,480
He pauses his work, looks up, and assumes with total seriousness and genuine enthusiasm

104
00:04:44,480 --> 00:04:49,620
that studying music theory must mean studying how music makes us feel things.

105
00:04:50,060 --> 00:04:54,860
Which, if you step outside the bubble of academia, is the most logical assumption a human being

106
00:04:54,860 --> 00:04:55,740
could possibly make.

107
00:04:55,800 --> 00:04:56,440
Totally is.

108
00:04:56,560 --> 00:04:57,920
I mean, why do we listen to music?

109
00:04:58,100 --> 00:04:59,200
Because it makes us feel.

110
00:04:59,420 --> 00:05:02,760
Therefore, the theory of music must be the study of those feelings.

111
00:05:02,760 --> 00:05:07,700
But Cox has to stand there and awkwardly explain, well, no, actually, I study the hierarchical

112
00:05:07,700 --> 00:05:09,540
relations among musical tones.

113
00:05:09,660 --> 00:05:11,080
Just crushing the guy's spirit.

114
00:05:11,360 --> 00:05:11,560
Yeah.

115
00:05:12,220 --> 00:05:15,800
He basically tells this guy, I studied the math of the invisible airwaves.

116
00:05:16,560 --> 00:05:21,800
And Cox notes that the conversation just died a quiet, uncomfortable little death right

117
00:05:21,800 --> 00:05:22,040
there.

118
00:05:22,280 --> 00:05:22,720
Awkward.

119
00:05:22,880 --> 00:05:26,940
The repairman went back to fixing the stove, probably thinking academia was completely useless.

120
00:05:27,320 --> 00:05:31,180
But that awkward interaction sparked a massive revelation for Cox.

121
00:05:31,180 --> 00:05:34,060
It really highlighted a glaring blind spot.

122
00:05:34,480 --> 00:05:39,620
Traditional musical analysis, staring at notes on a piece of paper, mapping out chord

123
00:05:39,620 --> 00:05:45,100
progressions, labeling syntax, completely misses the fundamental reason why human beings

124
00:05:45,100 --> 00:05:46,760
are drawn to music in the first place.

125
00:05:46,860 --> 00:05:47,060
Right.

126
00:05:47,360 --> 00:05:52,200
What the stove repairman intuitively understood in his gut, and what traditional theory was

127
00:05:52,200 --> 00:05:55,840
entirely missing, is the reality of the embodied mind.

128
00:05:55,880 --> 00:05:56,560
The embodied mind.

129
00:05:56,560 --> 00:06:03,140
For a very long time, cognitive science, philosophy, and musicology all treated the human brain like

130
00:06:03,140 --> 00:06:06,000
a disembodied computer sitting in a vat of fluid.

131
00:06:06,220 --> 00:06:07,620
Like a sci-fi brain in a jar.

132
00:06:07,780 --> 00:06:08,220
Exactly.

133
00:06:08,840 --> 00:06:10,660
The old model was highly mechanical.

134
00:06:11,520 --> 00:06:16,040
Sound waves enter the ear microphone, the brain computer processes the syntax of the audio

135
00:06:16,040 --> 00:06:19,120
data, and it outputs a cognitive understanding of the song.

136
00:06:19,220 --> 00:06:22,740
But I'm assuming that's not how millions of years of evolution actually designed us.

137
00:06:22,740 --> 00:06:23,620
Not even close.

138
00:06:23,740 --> 00:06:28,060
The brain didn't evolve to be a disembodied calculator analyzing abstract data streams.

139
00:06:28,260 --> 00:06:28,380
Right.

140
00:06:28,800 --> 00:06:33,540
To understand how we hear music, we have to rewind the evolutionary clock way back.

141
00:06:34,120 --> 00:06:37,820
Millions of years ago, life on Earth evolved without central nervous systems.

142
00:06:38,160 --> 00:06:39,180
Okay, so way, way back.

143
00:06:39,280 --> 00:06:39,440
Yeah.

144
00:06:39,820 --> 00:06:46,180
You had single-celled organisms and eventually simple multicellular organisms just floating

145
00:06:46,180 --> 00:06:48,160
around reacting to local stimuli.

146
00:06:48,320 --> 00:06:49,220
Like a sea sponge.

147
00:06:49,300 --> 00:06:50,160
It doesn't have a brain.

148
00:06:50,300 --> 00:06:51,820
It just exists and filters water.

149
00:06:51,820 --> 00:06:52,420
Exactly.

150
00:06:53,080 --> 00:06:58,500
But as organisms became massively multicellular and complex, developing specialized limbs,

151
00:06:58,700 --> 00:07:04,440
internal organs, digestive tracts, complex blood circulation, they encountered a massive

152
00:07:04,440 --> 00:07:05,500
biological problem.

153
00:07:05,640 --> 00:07:06,460
They needed a manager.

154
00:07:06,700 --> 00:07:10,720
They needed a centralized way to coordinate all these incredibly disparate parts.

155
00:07:10,840 --> 00:07:15,020
If the organism is being attacked, the muscles need to know to move, the heart needs to know

156
00:07:15,020 --> 00:07:18,080
to pump faster, the lungs need to take in more oxygen.

157
00:07:18,080 --> 00:07:22,680
So the central nervous system evolved to manage this complex bodily machinery.

158
00:07:22,920 --> 00:07:23,120
Yes.

159
00:07:23,360 --> 00:07:26,680
And its primary directive is to maintain homeostasis.

160
00:07:26,960 --> 00:07:28,640
I remember that term from high school biology.

161
00:07:29,180 --> 00:07:35,300
Homeostasis is that balanced, stable state where the organism is surviving, everything is

162
00:07:35,300 --> 00:07:37,320
functioning well, the engine is running smoothly.

163
00:07:37,640 --> 00:07:38,100
Precisely.

164
00:07:38,360 --> 00:07:39,560
And here's the crucial part.

165
00:07:39,560 --> 00:07:45,300
The mechanism the brain uses to maintain homeostasis is physical affect, feelings.

166
00:07:45,840 --> 00:07:49,520
Wait, you're saying emotions were basically the first management tool of the nervous system?

167
00:07:49,720 --> 00:07:50,740
Let's look at it practically.

168
00:07:51,480 --> 00:07:55,380
A drop in your blood sugar creates a negative affective state.

169
00:07:55,500 --> 00:07:55,800
Right.

170
00:07:55,880 --> 00:07:56,400
You get hungry.

171
00:07:56,400 --> 00:08:02,120
You experience it as a physical feeling of hunger, maybe a bit of lethargy or crankiness.

172
00:08:02,660 --> 00:08:04,020
That feeling is an abstract.

173
00:08:04,740 --> 00:08:06,980
It is a profound physical motivator.

174
00:08:07,540 --> 00:08:09,760
It drives an action, searching for food.

175
00:08:09,960 --> 00:08:12,000
You find an apple, you eat it.

176
00:08:12,480 --> 00:08:16,100
The digestion changes your blood chemistry, which restores homeostasis.

177
00:08:16,360 --> 00:08:21,600
And the brain rewards you with an agreeable affective state, the feeling of satisfaction.

178
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:22,260
Wow.

179
00:08:22,260 --> 00:08:27,700
Every single high-level cognitive function we possess today, our memory, our ability to

180
00:08:27,700 --> 00:08:33,260
plan for the future, our explicit abstract thoughts, all of it evolved layered on top

181
00:08:33,260 --> 00:08:37,200
of this fundamental primitive loop of physical affect and physical action.

182
00:08:37,380 --> 00:08:38,420
So what does this all mean?

183
00:08:38,540 --> 00:08:43,600
Are you saying my brain processing a Mozart sonata is built on the same evolutionary hardware

184
00:08:43,600 --> 00:08:47,680
as my brain deciding I need to eat an apple because my blood sugar is low?

185
00:08:47,960 --> 00:08:48,360
Yes.

186
00:08:48,360 --> 00:08:54,140
Your capacity to do advanced calculus or write a sonnet is running on an operating system

187
00:08:54,140 --> 00:08:57,980
originally designed to make you run away from a tiger or seek out a berry bush.

188
00:08:58,240 --> 00:09:00,320
That is a staggering way to frame it.

189
00:09:00,460 --> 00:09:05,660
So knowledge, thinking, and logic aren't these pure, isolated things operating in a vacuum.

190
00:09:05,980 --> 00:09:08,980
They're literally built out of the hardware of feeling and doing.

191
00:09:09,180 --> 00:09:09,660
They are.

192
00:09:09,920 --> 00:09:12,700
And musical meaning emerges from this exact combination.

193
00:09:12,700 --> 00:09:17,800
You cannot separate the acoustic sound of a cello from the physical affect and physical

194
00:09:17,800 --> 00:09:19,600
action it produces in your flesh.

195
00:09:19,800 --> 00:09:19,900
Right.

196
00:09:20,260 --> 00:09:25,700
The brain processing that Mozart sonata is the exact same biological organ that is constantly

197
00:09:25,700 --> 00:09:29,000
neurotically monitoring your body's survival states.

198
00:09:29,140 --> 00:09:29,320
Okay.

199
00:09:29,360 --> 00:09:32,860
That paints a brilliant picture of how interconnected the mind and body are.

200
00:09:33,060 --> 00:09:36,540
But it still leaves a really fascinating mechanical problem on the table.

201
00:09:36,680 --> 00:09:37,160
Which is?

202
00:09:37,160 --> 00:09:42,800
If my brain is this deeply anchored to the meat and bone of my body, how does a sound wave

203
00:09:42,800 --> 00:09:43,740
cross that border?

204
00:09:44,420 --> 00:09:47,660
A sound wave is just a disturbance of pressure propagating through the air.

205
00:09:47,940 --> 00:09:48,880
It hits my eardrum.

206
00:09:49,300 --> 00:09:53,340
How does that invisible vibration translate into the physical feeling of a pounding heart

207
00:09:53,340 --> 00:09:54,400
or exhausted limbs?

208
00:09:54,760 --> 00:09:59,920
To answer that, we have to introduce the most powerful tool in the human developmental toolkit,

209
00:10:00,660 --> 00:10:01,120
imitation.

210
00:10:01,780 --> 00:10:05,520
Or, as Cox frames it in the text, memetic behavior.

211
00:10:05,520 --> 00:10:07,240
You're talking about monkey see, monkey do.

212
00:10:07,580 --> 00:10:08,020
I am.

213
00:10:08,540 --> 00:10:12,520
But with human beings, and especially with music, it's also monkey see, monkey imagine.

214
00:10:12,720 --> 00:10:12,960
Okay.

215
00:10:13,680 --> 00:10:17,600
Cox introduces two crucial terms here that we need to keep in mind for the rest of this

216
00:10:17,600 --> 00:10:18,100
deep dive.

217
00:10:18,540 --> 00:10:22,840
The first is memetic motor action, which he abbreviates as MMA.

218
00:10:23,380 --> 00:10:23,640
Wow.

219
00:10:23,780 --> 00:10:26,020
This is overt, visible imitation.

220
00:10:26,620 --> 00:10:29,860
You see someone wave their hand, and you physically wave your hand back.

221
00:10:30,060 --> 00:10:32,520
You hear a beat, and you tap your foot out loud.

222
00:10:32,520 --> 00:10:34,060
So the action is externalized.

223
00:10:34,140 --> 00:10:35,560
Anyone in the room can see me doing it.

224
00:10:35,660 --> 00:10:35,960
Exactly.

225
00:10:36,360 --> 00:10:39,520
The second term is memetic motor imagery, or MMI.

226
00:10:39,720 --> 00:10:40,080
MMI.

227
00:10:40,240 --> 00:10:42,320
This is covert internal imitation.

228
00:10:42,800 --> 00:10:46,500
This is the invisible activity happening in the muscle-related portions of your brain

229
00:10:46,500 --> 00:10:51,780
when you imagine an action or observe an action, even if you don't move a single muscle

230
00:10:51,780 --> 00:10:52,400
outwardly.

231
00:10:52,800 --> 00:10:57,100
You are a statue on the outside, but internally, your brain's motor cortex is firing.

232
00:10:57,100 --> 00:11:01,960
So if I'm watching a gymnast do a backflip on TV, I'm sitting motionless on my couch

233
00:11:01,960 --> 00:11:07,180
eating potato chips, but part of my brain is covertly mapping out what it would take

234
00:11:07,180 --> 00:11:09,020
for my body to execute that backflip.

235
00:11:09,180 --> 00:11:09,900
Perfectly stated.

236
00:11:10,340 --> 00:11:15,400
And this memetic instinct, both overt and covert, isn't just a neat party trick.

237
00:11:15,700 --> 00:11:18,440
It is the literal foundation of human development.

238
00:11:18,680 --> 00:11:21,520
Right, because we don't just learn this in music appreciation class?

239
00:11:21,600 --> 00:11:24,100
No, we start doing it the second we are born.

240
00:11:24,100 --> 00:11:26,840
The text dies deep into infancy on this point.

241
00:11:27,720 --> 00:11:30,500
I mean, think about how a baby interacts with a parent.

242
00:11:30,960 --> 00:11:34,640
It is just a relentless, continuous loop of mutual imitation.

243
00:11:35,040 --> 00:11:37,360
It is the primary mode of early communication.

244
00:11:37,740 --> 00:11:42,940
The baby coos, the parent coos back, the parent smiles, the baby's face contorts to try and

245
00:11:42,940 --> 00:11:47,820
match the smile, and parents spontaneously model these exaggerated vocalizations.

246
00:11:48,400 --> 00:11:50,260
Linguists often call it motherese.

247
00:11:50,260 --> 00:11:55,460
Oh, that high-pitched, incredibly musical single-song voice, everyone automatically adopts the second

248
00:11:55,460 --> 00:11:56,460
they are handed a newborn.

249
00:11:56,580 --> 00:11:57,020
Exactly.

250
00:11:57,140 --> 00:11:57,980
Like, who's a good baby?

251
00:11:58,040 --> 00:11:58,640
Are you a good baby?

252
00:11:58,980 --> 00:12:02,360
The pitch just swings wildly up and down.

253
00:12:02,700 --> 00:12:07,060
Motherese has very specific, exaggerated pitch contours and rhythms.

254
00:12:07,500 --> 00:12:12,980
And the baby spends an enormous amount of energy trying to imitate those exact contours.

255
00:12:13,140 --> 00:12:13,360
Right.

256
00:12:13,360 --> 00:12:17,240
But what is deeply profound here is that the imitation goes both ways.

257
00:12:17,660 --> 00:12:19,920
The parents are obsessively imitating the infant.

258
00:12:20,260 --> 00:12:20,420
Wow.

259
00:12:21,020 --> 00:12:25,700
According to the developmental research cited in Cox's text, this mutual imitation is the

260
00:12:25,700 --> 00:12:27,200
bedrock of human psychology.

261
00:12:27,840 --> 00:12:33,280
When a caregiver physically mimics the facial expression or the vocal cry of a baby, it answers

262
00:12:33,280 --> 00:12:35,820
an incredibly deep, implicit need.

263
00:12:36,180 --> 00:12:40,080
It proves to the baby, I am capable of generating a response in others.

264
00:12:40,560 --> 00:12:42,520
Therefore, I exist and I am understood.

265
00:12:42,520 --> 00:12:42,860
Yes.

266
00:12:43,140 --> 00:12:46,380
It's not just about learning how to use vocal cords or facial muscles.

267
00:12:46,620 --> 00:12:48,380
It's the origin point of empathy.

268
00:12:48,780 --> 00:12:53,880
Because by imitating the baby's cry, the adult is essentially communicating, I feel what

269
00:12:53,880 --> 00:12:54,460
you are feeling.

270
00:12:54,600 --> 00:12:55,100
Exactly.

271
00:12:55,320 --> 00:12:57,560
They are enacting the physical exertions of the baby.

272
00:12:58,040 --> 00:13:02,760
And because we know physical exertions correlate with emotional states, the adult can actually

273
00:13:02,760 --> 00:13:05,880
use their own body to infer the emotional state of the child.

274
00:13:06,160 --> 00:13:11,720
And that primal desire, the need to understand others and be understood by them through shared

275
00:13:11,720 --> 00:13:14,960
physical states, doesn't just evaporate when we turn 18.

276
00:13:15,160 --> 00:13:15,920
Oh, definitely not.

277
00:13:15,980 --> 00:13:18,180
It just transforms and becomes more sophisticated.

278
00:13:18,720 --> 00:13:23,020
It becomes the basis for how we comprehend the actions of everyone around us in society.

279
00:13:23,020 --> 00:13:29,240
Whenever we observe someone doing something, our brain implicitly asks two deeply philosophical

280
00:13:29,240 --> 00:13:29,880
questions.

281
00:13:30,300 --> 00:13:31,540
What is it like to do that?

282
00:13:31,540 --> 00:13:34,760
And what is it like to be that entity?

283
00:13:34,760 --> 00:13:39,740
Which brings us to what might be my favorite part of this entire book, the most glorious,

284
00:13:40,080 --> 00:13:46,360
overt, uninhibited adult manifestation of this primal instinct, the air guitar phenomenon.

285
00:13:46,520 --> 00:13:51,980
It truly is the perfect, universally recognizable example of mimetic motor action in everyday adult

286
00:13:51,980 --> 00:13:52,360
life.

287
00:13:52,680 --> 00:13:55,340
Cox spends real academic time on this, and it's brilliant.

288
00:13:55,700 --> 00:14:00,580
You see people doing air guitar or air drumming on their steering wheel or full-blown lip syncing.

289
00:14:00,580 --> 00:14:04,340
The text actually references those early viral YouTube videos.

290
00:14:04,640 --> 00:14:06,000
Do you remember the Pneuma Pneuma guy?

291
00:14:06,220 --> 00:14:07,400
Oh, Gary Brolsma.

292
00:14:07,560 --> 00:14:08,040
Absolutely.

293
00:14:08,680 --> 00:14:08,920
Yes.

294
00:14:10,020 --> 00:14:14,780
Gary Brolsma, sitting in his computer chair, wearing his headset, vigorously pumping his

295
00:14:14,780 --> 00:14:18,240
fists, and aggressively lip syncing to a Romanian pop song.

296
00:14:18,520 --> 00:14:19,080
Iconic.

297
00:14:19,200 --> 00:14:20,460
Or the Chinese Backstreet Boys.

298
00:14:21,320 --> 00:14:26,800
Those two college kids, sitting in their dorm room, passionately miming every single vocal

299
00:14:26,800 --> 00:14:31,700
inflection of, I want it that way, while their roommate plays Counter-Strike in the background.

300
00:14:32,580 --> 00:14:35,040
Millions upon millions of people watch these videos.

301
00:14:35,480 --> 00:14:37,140
They were global sensations.

302
00:14:37,520 --> 00:14:40,660
Which raises an incredibly important psychological question.

303
00:14:40,940 --> 00:14:41,280
Why?

304
00:14:41,780 --> 00:14:45,000
Why do we enjoy watching someone else lip synced to a song?

305
00:14:45,100 --> 00:14:45,340
Yeah.

306
00:14:45,700 --> 00:14:47,580
If I want to hear the Axe Feet Boys, I have the CD.

307
00:14:47,760 --> 00:14:48,720
I can just put the track on.

308
00:14:48,720 --> 00:14:53,160
Why do I get so much joy out of watching two random college kids mime the lyrics?

309
00:14:53,560 --> 00:14:57,280
Well, the text suggests that watching them satisfies a deep mimetic urge.

310
00:14:57,760 --> 00:15:02,880
We enjoy seeing someone else enacting the physical participation that we secretly, subconsciously

311
00:15:02,880 --> 00:15:03,980
want to do ourselves.

312
00:15:04,160 --> 00:15:05,640
So they're doing the physical work for us.

313
00:15:05,880 --> 00:15:06,180
Right.

314
00:15:06,800 --> 00:15:10,480
Those guys in the dorm room are providing a first-order overt imitation.

315
00:15:10,840 --> 00:15:11,740
They are doing the MMA.

316
00:15:12,380 --> 00:15:16,700
And as viewers, we are engaging in a second-order covert imitation.

317
00:15:16,700 --> 00:15:19,700
We are vicariously participating in their vicarious participation.

318
00:15:20,540 --> 00:15:20,900
Oh, wow.

319
00:15:21,020 --> 00:15:25,020
When we see Gary Brolsma having the time of his life throwing his arms around to the

320
00:15:25,020 --> 00:15:30,060
Numa Numa song, it validates our own suppressed urges to embody the music.

321
00:15:30,200 --> 00:15:31,300
Okay, I love that.

322
00:15:31,480 --> 00:15:35,060
But if I'm playing the role of the skeptical listener right now, I have to challenge this

323
00:15:35,060 --> 00:15:35,320
a bit.

324
00:15:35,440 --> 00:15:35,900
Go for it.

325
00:15:36,160 --> 00:15:38,760
I understand singing along or lip syncing.

326
00:15:38,900 --> 00:15:39,700
I have vocal cords.

327
00:15:39,860 --> 00:15:40,320
I have lips.

328
00:15:40,460 --> 00:15:41,780
I know how to make human speech sounds.

329
00:15:42,180 --> 00:15:45,140
So when I lip sync, my imitation is mechanically accurate.

330
00:15:45,300 --> 00:15:45,540
Yeah.

331
00:15:45,540 --> 00:15:46,860
But air guitar.

332
00:15:47,220 --> 00:15:47,540
Yeah.

333
00:15:48,260 --> 00:15:50,260
I have never taken a guitar lesson in my life.

334
00:15:50,540 --> 00:15:52,080
I do not know how to play the instrument.

335
00:15:52,300 --> 00:15:56,140
If I play air guitar, I'm just blindly flailing my arms around in the air.

336
00:15:56,200 --> 00:15:56,520
Sure.

337
00:15:56,700 --> 00:16:00,220
My left hand is not forming actual cords on an invisible fretboard.

338
00:16:00,860 --> 00:16:06,800
How can my flailing possibly be considered cognition or genuine imitation if it's completely

339
00:16:06,800 --> 00:16:07,700
technically inaccurate?

340
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:09,980
That is a brilliant pushback.

341
00:16:10,140 --> 00:16:13,720
And the text explicitly addresses this apparent contradiction.

342
00:16:13,720 --> 00:16:19,900
What's fascinating here is that the exactness, the technical accuracy doesn't actually matter

343
00:16:19,900 --> 00:16:20,500
to the brain.

344
00:16:20,640 --> 00:16:21,080
It doesn't.

345
00:16:21,200 --> 00:16:21,480
No.

346
00:16:21,480 --> 00:16:26,620
Air guitar requires absolutely zero technical musical expertise.

347
00:16:27,180 --> 00:16:31,260
When you play air guitar, your imitation is trying to answer that subconscious question

348
00:16:31,260 --> 00:16:32,120
we mentioned earlier.

349
00:16:32,120 --> 00:16:33,960
What is it like to do that?

350
00:16:34,080 --> 00:16:38,660
What is it like to be the rock star making that incredible wailing sound?

351
00:16:38,800 --> 00:16:40,620
So my brain doesn't care about the fret placement.

352
00:16:40,740 --> 00:16:42,220
It just wants to capture the vibe.

353
00:16:42,380 --> 00:16:44,160
Vibe is a good colloquial term for it.

354
00:16:44,180 --> 00:16:46,300
But in cognitive science, we call it the schema.

355
00:16:46,680 --> 00:16:47,360
Schema, right?

356
00:16:47,360 --> 00:16:50,780
The text defines a schema as the overall pattern of energy.

357
00:16:50,780 --> 00:16:56,120
When you wildly strum your invisible guitar, you are imitating the rate of the rhythm, the

358
00:16:56,120 --> 00:17:01,020
intensity and violence of the strumming arm, the physical attitude, the facial contortions

359
00:17:01,020 --> 00:17:02,020
of the exertion.

360
00:17:02,120 --> 00:17:06,140
You are mapping the energy dynamics of the audio track onto your own body.

361
00:17:06,460 --> 00:17:06,980
Exactly.

362
00:17:07,300 --> 00:17:12,880
Even if your left hand is nowhere near a correct chord position, your gross motor movements

363
00:17:12,880 --> 00:17:18,160
are perfectly congruent with the effort and the passion of the actual guitarist on the

364
00:17:18,160 --> 00:17:18,540
recording.

365
00:17:18,600 --> 00:17:19,440
That makes perfect sense.

366
00:17:19,500 --> 00:17:19,620
Yeah.

367
00:17:19,620 --> 00:17:24,840
It's about simulating the feeling of the exertion, not the technical precision of the fingering.

368
00:17:25,320 --> 00:17:29,060
I'm feeling the aggression of a power chord, not the geometry of it.

369
00:17:29,140 --> 00:17:29,660
Precisely.

370
00:17:29,880 --> 00:17:30,000
Right.

371
00:17:30,120 --> 00:17:35,400
And this overt physical participation is incredibly rewarding to our nervous system.

372
00:17:35,520 --> 00:17:35,720
Yeah.

373
00:17:35,720 --> 00:17:41,180
We see this manifested culturally in the massive success of video games like Guitar Hero or

374
00:17:41,180 --> 00:17:41,820
Rock Band.

375
00:17:41,940 --> 00:17:43,180
Oh man, Guitar Hero.

376
00:17:43,640 --> 00:17:45,660
Think about the mechanics of those early games.

377
00:17:46,060 --> 00:17:51,340
The imitation was originally just pushing brightly colored plastic buttons on a fake plastic guitar.

378
00:17:51,580 --> 00:17:54,760
It looked nothing like playing a real Fender Stratocaster.

379
00:17:54,880 --> 00:17:55,280
Not at all.

380
00:17:55,340 --> 00:18:00,340
But it allowed millions of non-musicians to enjoy the aesthetic, physical and competitive

381
00:18:00,340 --> 00:18:02,720
rewards of successful memetic participation.

382
00:18:03,280 --> 00:18:04,720
People get fiercely competitive.

383
00:18:04,720 --> 00:18:06,240
Competitive of a guitar hero.

384
00:18:06,240 --> 00:18:11,800
And what's funny is, if you walk into a living room where people are playing rock band, the

385
00:18:11,800 --> 00:18:15,840
person playing the plastic guitar is almost always singing along with the lyrics too.

386
00:18:16,060 --> 00:18:16,500
Always.

387
00:18:16,500 --> 00:18:22,080
Even though the game doesn't score, they're singing, their hands are busy, but the urge to fully

388
00:18:22,080 --> 00:18:27,520
embody the music is just so overwhelmingly strong that their voice has to join in.

389
00:18:27,600 --> 00:18:29,480
It is a total bodily takeover.

390
00:18:29,600 --> 00:18:31,780
The memetic urge demands expression.

391
00:18:32,340 --> 00:18:32,640
Okay.

392
00:18:32,840 --> 00:18:37,880
So we have a really clear picture of what it looks like when we actively overtly participate.

393
00:18:37,880 --> 00:18:40,540
The air guitar, the lip cinching, the foot tapping.

394
00:18:40,720 --> 00:18:42,600
We are moving our bodies in space.

395
00:18:42,780 --> 00:18:42,820
Right.

396
00:18:43,140 --> 00:18:45,160
But let's take it a step further into the invisible.

397
00:18:45,160 --> 00:18:49,660
What is happening in the brain when we are sitting perfectly still on a crowded subway,

398
00:18:49,860 --> 00:18:52,060
wearing noise-canceling headphones, just listening?

399
00:18:52,260 --> 00:18:53,100
We are moving an inch.

400
00:18:53,200 --> 00:18:54,220
We aren't tapping a foot.

401
00:18:54,780 --> 00:19:00,580
How does the memetic hypothesis explain our reaction to music when we look completely passive?

402
00:19:00,580 --> 00:19:06,160
To understand the passive listener, we have to transition from MMA back to MMI, memetic

403
00:19:06,160 --> 00:19:06,920
motor imagery.

404
00:19:07,280 --> 00:19:12,520
We have to dive into the neurology of musical empathy, and that starts with one of the most

405
00:19:12,520 --> 00:19:17,840
famous neurological discoveries of the late 20th century, the mirror neuron system.

406
00:19:18,100 --> 00:19:19,780
Ah, the famous mirror neurons.

407
00:19:20,220 --> 00:19:25,100
I feel like these get brought up in every conversation about psychology or empathy, but how do they actually

408
00:19:25,100 --> 00:19:26,120
work in this context?

409
00:19:26,120 --> 00:19:32,100
Well, the initial neurological studies, which heavily utilized fMRI scans, revealed something

410
00:19:32,100 --> 00:19:33,920
astonishing about the primate brain.

411
00:19:34,280 --> 00:19:34,940
What did they find?

412
00:19:35,120 --> 00:19:41,200
They found that simply observing a goal-directed action lights up the exact same motor areas

413
00:19:41,200 --> 00:19:45,240
of the brain as if the observer were performing that action themselves.

414
00:19:45,400 --> 00:19:45,720
Wow.

415
00:19:46,140 --> 00:19:51,120
To use a simple example, if we are sitting across from each other and I watch you reach out,

416
00:19:51,120 --> 00:19:56,880
grasp a coffee mug and lift it to your mouth, the specific regions in my motor cortex that

417
00:19:56,880 --> 00:20:00,000
control my own hand, arm, and grasping fingers light up.

418
00:20:00,100 --> 00:20:00,900
Even though you aren't moving.

419
00:20:01,100 --> 00:20:01,380
Right.

420
00:20:01,680 --> 00:20:05,440
I'm not moving, but my brain is literally simulating your physical action.

421
00:20:05,760 --> 00:20:06,760
That is wild.

422
00:20:06,960 --> 00:20:09,700
My brain is essentially rehearsing your life in real time.

423
00:20:10,220 --> 00:20:10,660
Exactly.

424
00:20:10,840 --> 00:20:12,720
It is a covert simulation.

425
00:20:12,780 --> 00:20:16,080
Now, for a long time, this was primarily studied visually.

426
00:20:16,600 --> 00:20:18,220
Monkey see, monkey simulate.

427
00:20:18,220 --> 00:20:23,820
But the text cites several crucial studies demonstrating that this mirror system isn't

428
00:20:23,820 --> 00:20:24,840
strictly visual.

429
00:20:25,120 --> 00:20:26,640
It happens acoustically, too.

430
00:20:26,780 --> 00:20:30,800
We don't just mimic what we see, we vividly mimic what we hear.

431
00:20:30,920 --> 00:20:36,340
So if I'm blindfolded and I hear a sound, my brain still tries to simulate the physical

432
00:20:36,340 --> 00:20:37,840
action that created that sound.

433
00:20:37,960 --> 00:20:38,280
Yes.

434
00:20:38,920 --> 00:20:44,720
Cox references a landmark study by researchers Gazzola, Azizadeh, and Kiesers.

435
00:20:44,860 --> 00:20:45,600
How do they prove it?

436
00:20:45,600 --> 00:20:52,180
They put human participants inside fMRI machines and had them physically perform specific hand

437
00:20:52,180 --> 00:20:56,000
actions, like ripping a piece of paper in half or breaking a peanut shell.

438
00:20:56,420 --> 00:20:58,720
The machines recorded the motor cortex activity.

439
00:20:59,340 --> 00:21:03,380
Then they had those same participants lie perfectly still and just listen to audio recordings

440
00:21:03,380 --> 00:21:05,140
of paper ripping or peanuts breaking.

441
00:21:05,400 --> 00:21:08,220
And let me guess, the exact same motor areas lit up.

442
00:21:08,280 --> 00:21:09,100
Almost identically.

443
00:21:09,300 --> 00:21:13,360
Hearing the sound was entirely sufficient to trigger the motor simulation of the physical

444
00:21:13,360 --> 00:21:14,460
action that produced it.

445
00:21:14,760 --> 00:21:17,520
The auditory cortex talks directly to the motor cortex.

446
00:21:17,880 --> 00:21:19,220
So applying that to music.

447
00:21:20,220 --> 00:21:25,460
If the sound of a piano is physically the sound of human fingers striking wooden keys, then

448
00:21:25,460 --> 00:21:29,080
my brain simulates finger strikes when I hear a piano sonata.

449
00:21:29,280 --> 00:21:29,620
Yes.

450
00:21:30,140 --> 00:21:34,840
Your brain is running a silent, invisible simulation of finger movements.

451
00:21:34,840 --> 00:21:39,880
Now, the resolution of that simulation depends heavily on your own personal expertise, which

452
00:21:39,880 --> 00:21:40,880
we will get to later.

453
00:21:41,040 --> 00:21:41,220
Okay.

454
00:21:41,440 --> 00:21:46,380
But the most profound universal avenue for this acoustic mimicking isn't our fingers.

455
00:21:46,900 --> 00:21:48,160
It is the human voice.

456
00:21:48,560 --> 00:21:52,080
And this brings us to a concept called mimetic sub-vocalization.

457
00:21:52,460 --> 00:21:53,380
Sub-vocalization.

458
00:21:53,580 --> 00:21:53,700
Yeah.

459
00:21:53,700 --> 00:21:56,080
Literally silent singing beneath the voice.

460
00:21:56,300 --> 00:21:56,720
Exactly.

461
00:21:56,720 --> 00:22:02,240
Whenever we listen to someone speak or sing or yell, we are silently, subconsciously imitating

462
00:22:02,240 --> 00:22:03,740
them with our own vocal apparatus.

463
00:22:04,060 --> 00:22:04,440
Wait, really?

464
00:22:04,820 --> 00:22:05,080
Always?

465
00:22:05,380 --> 00:22:05,740
Always.

466
00:22:06,300 --> 00:22:10,060
The text references incredibly precise electromyography studies.

467
00:22:10,500 --> 00:22:14,660
That's where researchers attach sensors to measure the actual microscopic muscle electrical

468
00:22:14,660 --> 00:22:17,580
activity in the lips, larynx, and tongues of participants.

469
00:22:18,000 --> 00:22:18,280
Wow.

470
00:22:18,440 --> 00:22:22,940
When people listen to spoken words, even while sitting completely still and staring at a blank

471
00:22:22,940 --> 00:22:26,600
wall, the sensors picked up microactivations in their tongue and lip muscles.

472
00:22:26,920 --> 00:22:30,000
The muscles were actually firing, like trying to form the words.

473
00:22:30,180 --> 00:22:30,420
Yes.

474
00:22:30,940 --> 00:22:34,380
Excitation of the tongue muscles occurred just by listening to consonants.

475
00:22:34,880 --> 00:22:39,700
We are constantly, invisibly shadowing the sounds we hear with our own throats and mouths.

476
00:22:39,960 --> 00:22:42,900
That immediately makes me think of poetry and literature.

477
00:22:43,140 --> 00:22:43,800
Oh, absolutely.

478
00:22:44,260 --> 00:22:48,700
The text brings up Vladimir Nabokov's deeply controversial but linguistically brilliant novel,

479
00:22:49,140 --> 00:22:49,520
Lolita.

480
00:22:50,120 --> 00:22:54,240
There is that famous opening paragraph where the narrator is obsessing over the name.

481
00:22:54,240 --> 00:22:57,620
Lolita, light of my life, fire of my loins.

482
00:22:58,060 --> 00:22:59,440
My sin, my soul.

483
00:22:59,860 --> 00:23:03,960
The lid tip of the tongue, taking a trip of three steps down the palate to tap.

484
00:23:04,320 --> 00:23:05,620
At three, on the teeth.

485
00:23:05,800 --> 00:23:06,020
Lo.

486
00:23:06,400 --> 00:23:06,640
Li.

487
00:23:06,840 --> 00:23:07,280
Ah.

488
00:23:07,840 --> 00:23:12,400
It is a stunning example to bring up because Nabokov, whether he knew the neuroscience or

489
00:23:12,400 --> 00:23:17,740
not, is forcing the reader to become explicitly aware of their own physical, muscular act of

490
00:23:17,740 --> 00:23:18,540
sub-vocalization.

491
00:23:18,720 --> 00:23:19,180
Exactly.

492
00:23:19,460 --> 00:23:23,600
You literally cannot read that sentence silently without physically feeling your own tongue

493
00:23:23,600 --> 00:23:24,900
tapping the back of your front teeth.

494
00:23:24,900 --> 00:23:30,380
He is using the sensual, mechanical physicality of the words to make you memetically comprehend

495
00:23:30,380 --> 00:23:31,740
the narrator's physical obsession.

496
00:23:32,100 --> 00:23:34,020
He weaponizes sub-vocalization.

497
00:23:34,020 --> 00:23:40,780
You physically feel the words as you read them, and the exact same covert mirroring happens

498
00:23:40,780 --> 00:23:41,480
with music.

499
00:23:41,860 --> 00:23:47,200
When we hear a singer belting out a ballad, our vocal folds are microscopically tensing,

500
00:23:47,400 --> 00:23:50,180
stretching, and relaxing in total sympathy with them.

501
00:23:50,260 --> 00:23:50,480
Okay.

502
00:23:50,640 --> 00:23:52,540
But this raises a huge question.

503
00:23:53,180 --> 00:23:58,040
It's easy to understand sub-vocalizing a spoken word, or even a singer, in a normal range.

504
00:23:58,120 --> 00:23:58,380
Yeah.

505
00:23:58,380 --> 00:24:03,320
But what about sounds that aren't human voices, or sounds that defy human anatomy?

506
00:24:03,540 --> 00:24:03,780
Right.

507
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:08,220
The text mentions this incredible television commercial for Nike featuring LeBron James.

508
00:24:08,400 --> 00:24:08,620
Yes.

509
00:24:08,780 --> 00:24:13,860
The commercial from years ago, set to the instrumental funk track Summer Madness by Kool and the

510
00:24:13,860 --> 00:24:14,120
Gang.

511
00:24:14,240 --> 00:24:14,460
Right.

512
00:24:14,740 --> 00:24:16,520
If you haven't seen it, the commercial is gorgeous.

513
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:21,960
LeBron James is wearing a crisp white suit, and he is diving in extreme slow motion off a

514
00:24:21,960 --> 00:24:24,660
massively high diving platform into a swimming pool.

515
00:24:24,840 --> 00:24:25,320
Yes.

516
00:24:25,320 --> 00:24:29,280
And as he falls through the air, this iconic synthesizer note in the Kool and the Gang

517
00:24:29,280 --> 00:24:30,680
track just starts climbing.

518
00:24:30,980 --> 00:24:35,400
It sweeps higher and higher, this continuous ascending glissando, until it ends on this

519
00:24:35,400 --> 00:24:38,060
incredibly piercing high Eshtar 7 note.

520
00:24:38,140 --> 00:24:39,040
It's an iconic moment.

521
00:24:39,360 --> 00:24:41,280
Now, here's where it gets really interesting.

522
00:24:42,140 --> 00:24:42,960
I have tried.

523
00:24:43,620 --> 00:24:46,600
I physically cannot sing an Eshtar 7.

524
00:24:47,120 --> 00:24:49,920
My vocal cords do not go anywhere near that high.

525
00:24:49,960 --> 00:24:50,180
Right.

526
00:24:50,260 --> 00:24:51,240
Most people's don't.

527
00:24:51,240 --> 00:24:58,080
So how on earth can my brain be sub-vocalizing a synthesizer note that is biologically impossible

528
00:24:58,080 --> 00:24:59,400
for my body to produce?

529
00:24:59,400 --> 00:25:01,400
That is the edge case that proves the rule.

530
00:25:01,980 --> 00:25:06,780
If sub-vocalization is entirely based on mapping sound to our own physical experience,

531
00:25:07,260 --> 00:25:08,700
how do we mimic the impossible?

532
00:25:09,180 --> 00:25:10,920
How do we map a synthesizer?

533
00:25:11,020 --> 00:25:11,480
Yeah, how?

534
00:25:11,760 --> 00:25:16,160
The text suggests that the human brain has an incredible capacity to extrapolate.

535
00:25:16,460 --> 00:25:18,220
We imagine doing more of the same.

536
00:25:18,280 --> 00:25:19,740
What does that mean, more of the same?

537
00:25:19,740 --> 00:25:23,640
Well, you know what it feels like to stretch your vocal folds to reach the highest note

538
00:25:23,640 --> 00:25:24,200
you can sing?

539
00:25:24,700 --> 00:25:28,800
You know the physical sensation of that strain in your neck, the tightness in your larynx?

540
00:25:29,000 --> 00:25:30,020
Yeah, I know that feeling.

541
00:25:30,300 --> 00:25:35,100
When the synthesizer continues to ascend past your physical breaking point, your brain doesn't

542
00:25:35,100 --> 00:25:36,460
just shut off the simulation.

543
00:25:36,980 --> 00:25:41,900
It takes that feeling of muscular stretching and effort, and it just keeps pushing it internally.

544
00:25:42,220 --> 00:25:44,720
It mathematically extrapolates the effort.

545
00:25:45,140 --> 00:25:45,440
Oh.

546
00:25:45,440 --> 00:25:50,860
So my brain is imagining what it would feel like if my vocal cords were made of rubber and

547
00:25:50,860 --> 00:25:53,400
could just keep stretching indefinitely without snapping.

548
00:25:53,640 --> 00:25:54,120
Exactly.

549
00:25:54,500 --> 00:25:58,040
You are simulating an impossible bodily state.

550
00:25:58,380 --> 00:26:08,240
And the effective result of that, the emotional feeling it generates in your mind, is this incredibly thrilling sensation of transcending your own bodily limitations.

551
00:26:08,240 --> 00:26:15,760
You are experiencing a superhuman effort, a feeling of flying or defying gravity, achieved entirely

552
00:26:15,760 --> 00:26:17,560
through memetic motor imagery.

553
00:26:17,800 --> 00:26:22,460
That is why that synthesizer sweep makes the slow motion dive feel so epic.

554
00:26:22,640 --> 00:26:24,980
You are vicariously breaking the laws of physics.

555
00:26:25,120 --> 00:26:26,820
That is just so cool.

556
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:30,620
I am vicariously breaking the laws of human anatomy through a synthesizer.

557
00:26:30,640 --> 00:26:31,280
You really are.

558
00:26:31,280 --> 00:26:34,560
So we are constantly, invisibly mirroring the music we hear.

559
00:26:35,000 --> 00:26:38,820
But obviously, if I put my playlist on shuffle, not all sounds are asking to be mirrored in

560
00:26:38,820 --> 00:26:39,600
the exact same way.

561
00:26:39,680 --> 00:26:43,100
A heavy metal song and a lullaby are asking my body for very different things.

562
00:26:43,160 --> 00:26:43,540
They are.

563
00:26:43,700 --> 00:26:48,500
And that leads us to a central framework in Cox's book, The Concept of the Mimetic Invitation.

564
00:26:48,980 --> 00:26:49,760
I love this framing.

565
00:26:50,040 --> 00:26:50,640
An invitation.

566
00:26:50,640 --> 00:26:56,880
The text argues that every single piece of music issues an invitation to the listener

567
00:26:56,880 --> 00:26:57,540
to participate.

568
00:26:58,420 --> 00:27:03,440
And as listeners, we intuitively evaluate music based on what it is inviting us to do.

569
00:27:03,560 --> 00:27:03,840
Yes.

570
00:27:04,060 --> 00:27:08,620
The primary metrics we use to evaluate these invitations are singability and danceability.

571
00:27:09,160 --> 00:27:14,340
Music that is easily singable usually features a clear, stepwise melody, meaning the notes are

572
00:27:14,340 --> 00:27:18,200
close together, a limited vocal range, and simple, predictable rhythms.

573
00:27:18,360 --> 00:27:18,580
Okay.

574
00:27:18,580 --> 00:27:24,560
Easily danceable music has a pronounced, regular beat and a tempo that affords efficient, comfortable,

575
00:27:24,840 --> 00:27:25,860
whole body movements.

576
00:27:26,100 --> 00:27:30,920
So if a massive pop song by Taylor Swift or The Weeknd comes on the radio, it is sending

577
00:27:30,920 --> 00:27:33,740
out a very clear, very demanding RSVP.

578
00:27:33,920 --> 00:27:38,120
Like, hey, tap your foot to this incredibly regular beat and hum along to this incredibly

579
00:27:38,120 --> 00:27:39,800
catchy mid-range chorus.

580
00:27:39,920 --> 00:27:40,400
Precisely.

581
00:27:40,600 --> 00:27:42,320
It is an easy invitation to accept.

582
00:27:42,700 --> 00:27:46,680
And our aesthetic preference, meaning whether we actually like the song or think it's annoying,

583
00:27:46,680 --> 00:27:50,960
often depends entirely on whether we want to inhabit the physical state that the music

584
00:27:50,960 --> 00:27:52,520
is inviting us into at that moment.

585
00:27:52,660 --> 00:27:53,440
Ah, that makes sense.

586
00:27:53,740 --> 00:27:56,540
The text provides a brilliant comparative example.

587
00:27:57,120 --> 00:28:02,460
Julie Andrews singing the classic show tune, My Favorite Things, versus the legendary saxophonist

588
00:28:02,460 --> 00:28:05,500
John Coltrane's jazz rendition of that exact same song.

589
00:28:05,500 --> 00:28:07,380
Oh, that is the perfect contrast.

590
00:28:07,540 --> 00:28:12,260
Julie Andrews, in The Sound of Music, is very crisp, clear, straightforward.

591
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:14,640
Every syllable is enunciated.

592
00:28:15,060 --> 00:28:16,060
It is highly singable.

593
00:28:16,140 --> 00:28:16,340
Right.

594
00:28:16,760 --> 00:28:20,480
Coltrane's version, on the other hand, takes that simple melody and shatters it.

595
00:28:20,480 --> 00:28:25,980
It is harmonically complex, rhythmically elaborate, constantly pushing the boundaries of tempo

596
00:28:25,980 --> 00:28:26,720
and structure.

597
00:28:26,720 --> 00:28:31,460
They are playing the same underlying composition, but they issue vastly different physical invitations

598
00:28:31,460 --> 00:28:32,240
to the listener.

599
00:28:32,980 --> 00:28:37,320
Andrews invites a relatively constrained, straightforward, joyful embodiment.

600
00:28:37,620 --> 00:28:39,920
You know exactly where to put your feet and your voice.

601
00:28:40,160 --> 00:28:40,340
Yeah.

602
00:28:40,620 --> 00:28:46,120
Coltrane invites a much more complex, unpredictable, elaborate, and perhaps even chaotic, memetic

603
00:28:46,120 --> 00:28:46,720
engagement.

604
00:28:47,300 --> 00:28:51,220
Your internal simulation has to work overtime to track his saxophone lines.

605
00:28:51,220 --> 00:28:55,580
So, if I prefer the Coltrane version, it is partly because I actually enjoy the complex

606
00:28:55,580 --> 00:28:59,220
physical and mental gymnastics it forces my brain to simulate?

607
00:28:59,740 --> 00:29:00,060
Yes.

608
00:29:00,880 --> 00:29:03,480
You enjoy the cognitive and memetic workout.

609
00:29:03,960 --> 00:29:09,420
But if you dislike the Coltrane version, it might be because you find that complex, memetic

610
00:29:09,420 --> 00:29:13,000
invitation exhausting, abrasive, or confusing.

611
00:29:13,400 --> 00:29:17,160
You don't want to do the internal work it demands, so you reject the song.

612
00:29:17,160 --> 00:29:21,840
And it isn't just about the vocal cords tracking a melody or the foot tapping to a snare drum.

613
00:29:22,520 --> 00:29:24,920
This is where the text completely blew my mind.

614
00:29:25,300 --> 00:29:29,020
It moves beyond the extremities and introduces a modal imitation.

615
00:29:29,420 --> 00:29:29,720
Yes.

616
00:29:29,980 --> 00:29:35,760
A modal meaning it isn't specific to a single sensory mode or a specific limb like the hands

617
00:29:35,760 --> 00:29:36,580
or the voice.

618
00:29:36,900 --> 00:29:41,520
It refers to the center of mass, the core, the abdominal muscles, the diaphragm.

619
00:29:41,580 --> 00:29:41,800
Right.

620
00:29:41,980 --> 00:29:46,020
If you're listening right now, you might be thinking, I don't flex my abs when a pop song

621
00:29:46,020 --> 00:29:47,400
comes on, I'm just driving my car.

622
00:29:47,500 --> 00:29:47,680
Sure.

623
00:29:47,880 --> 00:29:52,360
But the text points out that every single time a drummer hits a crash cymbal with force

624
00:29:52,360 --> 00:29:57,420
or a brass player blows a massive loud note or an opera singer belts a soaring aria, the

625
00:29:57,420 --> 00:29:59,120
performer has to flex their core.

626
00:29:59,260 --> 00:29:59,800
They do.

627
00:29:59,800 --> 00:30:05,140
They have to engage their abdominal muscles to anchor that physical exertion and push the

628
00:30:05,140 --> 00:30:05,560
air out.

629
00:30:06,340 --> 00:30:10,240
And because we are memetically mirroring them, because we're asking what is it like to be

630
00:30:10,240 --> 00:30:15,800
the person making that sound, we actually feel that clenching and relaxing in our own gut.

631
00:30:16,020 --> 00:30:19,820
It is a deeply visceral, completely subconscious reaction.

632
00:30:20,260 --> 00:30:24,680
The overall energy dynamics of the music, the swelling crescendos, the violent crashes,

633
00:30:24,680 --> 00:30:30,740
the intense, silent holds are perfectly mirrored in the tension of our own abdominal muscles and

634
00:30:30,740 --> 00:30:31,760
our respiratory rate.

635
00:30:32,180 --> 00:30:34,120
We quite literally have a gut reaction to the music.

636
00:30:34,180 --> 00:30:34,600
Exactly.

637
00:30:34,800 --> 00:30:35,760
We breathe with it.

638
00:30:35,860 --> 00:30:36,740
We clench with it.

639
00:30:36,880 --> 00:30:41,800
This connects so perfectly to the story of Evelyn Glennie, the profoundly deaf percussionist

640
00:30:41,800 --> 00:30:42,620
the text mentions.

641
00:30:42,620 --> 00:30:43,060
Yes.

642
00:30:43,380 --> 00:30:45,200
Dame Evelyn Glennie is a phenomenal example.

643
00:30:45,360 --> 00:30:50,660
Because she is deaf, she experiences acoustic sound not as auditory information decoded in

644
00:30:50,660 --> 00:30:56,580
the ear, but as physical touch, raw vibrations felt through her bare feet on the floorboards

645
00:30:56,580 --> 00:30:58,720
and through the resonance in her chest and stomach.

646
00:30:59,100 --> 00:31:01,660
It proves that sound is a physical impact event.

647
00:31:02,220 --> 00:31:05,920
We all have the biological capacity to feel music physically.

648
00:31:06,360 --> 00:31:06,720
Yeah.

649
00:31:06,940 --> 00:31:10,260
Glennie just relies on it profoundly to perform and understand the music.

650
00:31:10,260 --> 00:31:10,600
Right.

651
00:31:10,880 --> 00:31:14,560
But we are all feeling those heavy bass notes and cymbal crashes in our chest and gut,

652
00:31:14,660 --> 00:31:18,960
even if we are primarily distracted by hearing them through our ears.

653
00:31:19,120 --> 00:31:20,880
But this raises another interesting challenge.

654
00:31:20,980 --> 00:31:23,900
We've talked about pop songs and jazz and heavy drums.

655
00:31:24,200 --> 00:31:28,520
What about music that actively resists any kind of bodily participation?

656
00:31:29,100 --> 00:31:31,400
What about music that gives you nothing to hold on to?

657
00:31:31,500 --> 00:31:31,660
Right.

658
00:31:31,800 --> 00:31:32,760
The ambient stuff.

659
00:31:32,840 --> 00:31:33,020
Yeah.

660
00:31:33,020 --> 00:31:38,940
The text brings up the avant-garde composer Gjörgy Ligeti, specifically his piece Atmospheres,

661
00:31:39,320 --> 00:31:42,720
which famously featured in the movie 2001, A Space Odyssey.

662
00:31:42,920 --> 00:31:43,740
Ah, yes.

663
00:31:43,800 --> 00:31:48,800
If you haven't heard it, it is essentially a giant, static, slowly shifting mass of microtonal

664
00:31:48,800 --> 00:31:49,260
sound.

665
00:31:49,980 --> 00:31:51,720
There is no beat to tap your foot to.

666
00:31:51,800 --> 00:31:52,960
There is no melody to hum.

667
00:31:53,260 --> 00:31:56,520
It is just a terrifying, creeping wall of sonic fog.

668
00:31:56,800 --> 00:32:00,160
How on earth do we mimetically participate with a wall of fog?

669
00:32:00,380 --> 00:32:01,300
It's a great question.

670
00:32:01,300 --> 00:32:06,740
Arnie Cox notes in the book that for years, he used Ligeti's Atmospheres in his classes

671
00:32:06,740 --> 00:32:10,500
as the ultimate example of music with a zero-degree memetic invitation.

672
00:32:11,040 --> 00:32:12,800
He thought it was the exception to his own rule.

673
00:32:13,060 --> 00:32:13,440
Oh, you're right.

674
00:32:13,500 --> 00:32:17,920
But then one day, a student in his class was listening to the piece, and she raised her

675
00:32:17,920 --> 00:32:20,460
hand and said, I don't know, it kind of makes me want to do this.

676
00:32:20,500 --> 00:32:26,640
And she very, very slowly extended both of her arms outward, stretching them wide, and

677
00:32:26,640 --> 00:32:28,860
slowly rotated her head and torso.

678
00:32:29,260 --> 00:32:29,620
Wow.

679
00:32:29,620 --> 00:32:36,560
So even with a wall of sound, she found a way to embody the slow, massive expansion of

680
00:32:36,560 --> 00:32:37,400
the acoustic energy.

681
00:32:37,460 --> 00:32:37,900
Exactly.

682
00:32:38,060 --> 00:32:38,840
It was a revelation.

683
00:32:39,480 --> 00:32:42,900
It shows that the memetic invitation never truly drops to zero.

684
00:32:43,160 --> 00:32:48,680
Even with ambient, atmospheric, beatless music, our nervous system is so desperate to connect

685
00:32:48,680 --> 00:32:52,380
that we will find a way to map its energy dynamics onto our bodies.

686
00:32:52,460 --> 00:32:53,800
Even if the movement is weird.

687
00:32:53,900 --> 00:32:54,120
Right.

688
00:32:54,120 --> 00:32:58,760
Even if the resulting physical movement is non-normative, slow, or extremely abstract.

689
00:32:58,980 --> 00:33:03,920
And this instinct, this desperate drive to map the energy of the world onto our own muscles,

690
00:33:04,340 --> 00:33:06,020
extends way beyond music.

691
00:33:06,280 --> 00:33:09,700
This is where Cox tells the story about the wood splitter, which is just brilliant.

692
00:33:09,940 --> 00:33:16,580
It is a fantastic demonstration of how far our memetic empathy reaches into the non-human

693
00:33:16,580 --> 00:33:16,940
world.

694
00:33:17,440 --> 00:33:19,140
So picture this scene.

695
00:33:19,800 --> 00:33:24,080
Cox and his brother are out in the yard chopping firewood for the winter, but they aren't using

696
00:33:24,080 --> 00:33:24,560
axes.

697
00:33:25,100 --> 00:33:29,860
They're using a massive, motorized, 43-ton hydraulic wood splitter.

698
00:33:29,920 --> 00:33:30,240
Right.

699
00:33:30,240 --> 00:33:36,660
It's this terrifying, loud piece of heavy machinery that just slowly, inexorably pushes a steel

700
00:33:36,660 --> 00:33:38,720
wedge through giant, solid oak logs.

701
00:33:38,960 --> 00:33:41,340
It crunches and groans as it shreds the wood.

702
00:33:41,940 --> 00:33:45,760
And as they are working, his brother keeps watching the machine operate, clenching his fist,

703
00:33:46,120 --> 00:33:50,080
and yelling, feel the power, feel the power, over the noise of the engine.

704
00:33:50,240 --> 00:33:52,320
They are empathizing with the hydraulic press.

705
00:33:52,720 --> 00:33:54,740
Now, obviously, a machine does not have feelings.

706
00:33:54,840 --> 00:33:56,360
It doesn't have a soul or a nervous system.

707
00:33:56,480 --> 00:33:58,960
There is no consciousness there to actually empathize with.

708
00:33:58,960 --> 00:33:59,180
Right.

709
00:33:59,260 --> 00:34:00,680
The machine isn't trying to do anything.

710
00:34:00,800 --> 00:34:01,840
It's just fluid dynamics.

711
00:34:02,240 --> 00:34:06,180
But what is happening in the brother's brain is that he is imagining what it would be like

712
00:34:06,180 --> 00:34:06,860
to be the machine.

713
00:34:06,860 --> 00:34:13,300
He is projecting his own human bodily sense of muscular effort, strain, and eventual

714
00:34:13,300 --> 00:34:16,640
achievement onto the mechanical action of the steel wedge.

715
00:34:17,160 --> 00:34:17,940
That makes total sense.

716
00:34:18,060 --> 00:34:23,720
He is watching the wood splinter and feeling the awe of that massive physical exertion vicariously

717
00:34:23,720 --> 00:34:25,320
in his own chest and arms.

718
00:34:25,320 --> 00:34:27,240
We anthropomorphize the energy.

719
00:34:27,820 --> 00:34:32,040
And we do this with the most mundane, silent things, too, not just loud machinery.

720
00:34:32,840 --> 00:34:35,460
The text talks about empathizing with printing fonts.

721
00:34:35,680 --> 00:34:35,980
Yes.

722
00:34:36,420 --> 00:34:40,720
Typography offers a perfect visual equivalent to the acoustic memetic invitation.

723
00:34:41,080 --> 00:34:42,320
I found this so relatable.

724
00:34:42,800 --> 00:34:47,440
The text points out that we have genuine, physical, effective reactions to seeing bold or

725
00:34:47,440 --> 00:34:49,180
italic fonts on a page or screen.

726
00:34:49,340 --> 00:34:49,740
We do.

727
00:34:49,740 --> 00:34:54,840
When you get a text message or read a headline printed in heavy, bold, all-caps font, you

728
00:34:54,840 --> 00:34:56,680
don't just read it louder in your inner monologue.

729
00:34:57,280 --> 00:35:02,220
Your brain actually simulates the physical energy required to drag a heavy marker to draw

730
00:35:02,220 --> 00:35:03,680
those thick, dark lines.

731
00:35:04,100 --> 00:35:08,860
Or it simulates the physical respiratory effort required to shout those words across a room.

732
00:35:09,180 --> 00:35:12,960
It fundamentally alters the motor imagery of your sublocalization.

733
00:35:12,960 --> 00:35:26,000
So whether it is a deaf percussionist feeling the vibrations in the floorboards, a college

734
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:31,080
student slowly extending her arms to a Legetti soundscape, my brother yelling at a hydraulic

735
00:35:31,080 --> 00:35:37,520
wood splitter, or me getting stressed out by a bold font email from my boss, our bodies

736
00:35:37,520 --> 00:35:42,620
are constantly, relentlessly striving to mirror the energy of the world around us.

737
00:35:43,020 --> 00:35:43,940
It is inescapable.

738
00:35:44,360 --> 00:35:47,620
But everything we have discussed so far in this deep dive is fairly isolated.

739
00:35:47,760 --> 00:35:49,140
One listener reacting to one singer.

740
00:35:49,520 --> 00:35:51,000
One listener reacting to one machine.

741
00:35:51,520 --> 00:35:54,920
To really test the limits of this theory, we have to look at what happens when the source

742
00:35:54,920 --> 00:35:55,920
material multiplies.

743
00:35:56,080 --> 00:35:58,180
What happens when there are 50 people on stage?

744
00:35:58,240 --> 00:35:58,600
Yes.

745
00:35:59,300 --> 00:36:00,300
The symphony orchestra.

746
00:36:00,840 --> 00:36:01,740
The massive choir.

747
00:36:02,100 --> 00:36:04,320
How does the memetic hypothesis handle a crowd?

748
00:36:04,540 --> 00:36:05,480
That's a great question.

749
00:36:05,480 --> 00:36:11,520
If my brain is biologically wired to mirror the performer, what happens when I put on

750
00:36:11,520 --> 00:36:14,360
my headphones and listen to a balked two-part invention?

751
00:36:14,740 --> 00:36:19,800
You have two completely independent piano melodies weaving in and out of each other simultaneously.

752
00:36:20,460 --> 00:36:22,220
I only have one inner voice.

753
00:36:22,640 --> 00:36:26,420
I can't sub-vocalize two different melodies at the exact same time.

754
00:36:26,640 --> 00:36:28,440
Does my brain just crash like a computer?

755
00:36:28,940 --> 00:36:29,660
Not at all.

756
00:36:30,120 --> 00:36:32,560
The text has a fascinating explanation for this.

757
00:36:32,560 --> 00:36:39,040
In cases like a two-part invention or a small string quartet, our memetic participation rapidly,

758
00:36:39,300 --> 00:36:43,000
subconsciously jumps back and forth between the distinct melodies.

759
00:36:43,320 --> 00:36:46,340
The author compares it to visual secades.

760
00:36:46,560 --> 00:36:47,340
Visual secades.

761
00:36:47,440 --> 00:36:47,940
What are those?

762
00:36:48,220 --> 00:36:53,320
Secades are the rapid, involuntary, jerky eye movements we make when we are looking at

763
00:36:53,320 --> 00:36:56,500
something, like scanning a painting or looking at a person's face.

764
00:36:56,580 --> 00:36:58,480
Oh, like when we jump from point to point.

765
00:36:58,480 --> 00:37:01,980
You don't just stare blankly at the exact center of a face and absorb the whole thing

766
00:37:01,980 --> 00:37:02,440
at once.

767
00:37:02,760 --> 00:37:06,540
Your eyes dart rapidly from the left eye to the right eye to the mouth to the hairline,

768
00:37:06,940 --> 00:37:07,960
piecing the image together.

769
00:37:08,340 --> 00:37:09,740
Okay, so auditory secades.

770
00:37:10,560 --> 00:37:16,600
My auditory attention and my internal sub-vocalization is darting back and forth between the high melody

771
00:37:16,600 --> 00:37:21,760
and the low bass line, actively engaging with whichever one holds my focus at that microsecond.

772
00:37:21,860 --> 00:37:22,240
Exactly.

773
00:37:22,640 --> 00:37:24,980
You are rapidly switching your memetic allegiance.

774
00:37:24,980 --> 00:37:28,040
But what if we scale it up even further?

775
00:37:28,540 --> 00:37:31,280
What if it isn't just two lines or four?

776
00:37:31,520 --> 00:37:35,600
What if it is Thomas Tallis' famous composition, Spem, in Allium?

777
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:36,380
Oh, wow.

778
00:37:36,660 --> 00:37:40,880
That's the Renaissance motet written for 40 completely independent singing voices.

779
00:37:41,160 --> 00:37:43,260
40 different vocal lines happening at once.

780
00:37:43,420 --> 00:37:43,680
Yes.

781
00:37:44,020 --> 00:37:48,500
In that scenario, your brain simply cannot perform secades fast enough to jump between 40 voices.

782
00:37:48,760 --> 00:37:50,660
It is biologically impossible to track.

783
00:37:50,960 --> 00:37:51,500
So what do we do?

784
00:37:51,560 --> 00:37:52,160
Do we give up?

785
00:37:52,380 --> 00:37:52,760
No.

786
00:37:52,760 --> 00:37:57,840
The text argues that in these overwhelming ensemble situations, we shift our strategy.

787
00:37:58,400 --> 00:38:00,360
We no longer follow an individual voice.

788
00:38:00,540 --> 00:38:04,960
Instead, we memetically mirror the composite emergent musical entity.

789
00:38:05,180 --> 00:38:06,060
The composite entity.

790
00:38:06,460 --> 00:38:11,940
So I'm treating the entire 40-person choir as if it were one giant, multi-lunged organism.

791
00:38:11,940 --> 00:38:12,900
Precisely.

792
00:38:13,280 --> 00:38:20,620
You mirror the overall metric schema, the shared rhythmic pulse, the general massive wave of vocal exertion.

793
00:38:20,840 --> 00:38:23,260
You aren't imitating 40 individuals.

794
00:38:23,580 --> 00:38:28,020
You are imitating the choir as a single breathing entity.

795
00:38:28,220 --> 00:38:29,080
That makes total sense.

796
00:38:29,400 --> 00:38:30,740
We zoom out to the macro level.

797
00:38:30,740 --> 00:38:36,260
Now, does my personal background change how I perform this mirroring?

798
00:38:36,260 --> 00:38:43,120
If I am a trained musician versus someone who just listens to the radio, am I mirroring that choir or that orchestra differently?

799
00:38:43,380 --> 00:38:43,780
Absolutely.

800
00:38:44,180 --> 00:38:47,100
Expertise profoundly changes the physical mechanics of listening.

801
00:38:47,360 --> 00:38:50,240
The text points to some incredible neurological studies that confirm this.

802
00:38:50,300 --> 00:38:50,460
Okay.

803
00:38:50,640 --> 00:38:50,920
Like what?

804
00:38:51,180 --> 00:39:00,940
In one fMRI study, researchers looked at the brains of expert, professionally trained pianists and compared them to non-pianists, while both groups just passively listened to piano music.

805
00:39:00,940 --> 00:39:01,780
And what did they find?

806
00:39:02,200 --> 00:39:05,700
The motor cortex of the expert pianists lit up significantly more.

807
00:39:05,700 --> 00:39:19,200
Because they had spent thousands of hours physically moving their fingers across keys, their brains possessed a much richer, more highly detailed, high-resolution motor map of what it takes to produce those specific acoustic sounds.

808
00:39:19,540 --> 00:39:21,560
They weren't just generally feeling the rhythm.

809
00:39:22,100 --> 00:39:25,600
Their brains were intensely simulating the precise finger movements.

810
00:39:25,600 --> 00:39:32,060
Oh, and this completely explains that other study mentioned in the text, the interference study by Drost and his colleagues.

811
00:39:32,220 --> 00:39:33,100
I love this one.

812
00:39:33,220 --> 00:39:33,440
Yes.

813
00:39:33,700 --> 00:39:36,940
The Drost study is a perfect demonstration of intramodal imitation.

814
00:39:37,400 --> 00:39:40,580
So let me describe this experiment because it is so clever.

815
00:39:41,320 --> 00:39:45,360
The researchers took a group of musicians, some guitarists and some pianists.

816
00:39:45,640 --> 00:39:52,960
They sat them down and instructed them to silently play a specific chord on their own instrument as fast as they could when prompted.

817
00:39:53,220 --> 00:39:53,500
Right.

818
00:39:53,500 --> 00:40:02,280
But right as they were supposed to play their silent chord, the researchers would blast an audio recording of a different clashing chord in their ears.

819
00:40:02,340 --> 00:40:02,640
Right.

820
00:40:02,840 --> 00:40:04,300
They created a cognitive conflict.

821
00:40:04,560 --> 00:40:04,940
Exactly.

822
00:40:05,440 --> 00:40:12,620
If the musician was supposed to play a major chord, but the audio played a dissonant minor chord, it caused an interference effect.

823
00:40:13,060 --> 00:40:16,220
It caused a measurable delay in their reaction time.

824
00:40:16,680 --> 00:40:17,620
Their fingers stumbled.

825
00:40:18,340 --> 00:40:19,860
But here is the crazy part.

826
00:40:19,860 --> 00:40:25,480
This interference only happened if the conflicting audio chord was played on the musician's own instrument.

827
00:40:25,580 --> 00:40:27,020
That is the key finding.

828
00:40:27,420 --> 00:40:35,660
If a pianist was told to play a chord and they heard a conflicting dissonant chord played on a guitar, they didn't stumble at all.

829
00:40:35,780 --> 00:40:37,380
Their reaction time was perfect.

830
00:40:37,500 --> 00:40:43,140
Because the acoustic sound of the guitar didn't trigger the pianist's specific high-resolution,

831
00:40:43,140 --> 00:40:46,940
mimetic motor imagery strongly enough to interfere with their fingers.

832
00:40:47,060 --> 00:40:47,960
That is wild.

833
00:40:47,960 --> 00:40:53,000
Their brain heard the guitar and essentially said, that is a guitar's physical problem.

834
00:40:53,200 --> 00:40:53,900
We are a piano.

835
00:40:54,160 --> 00:40:54,700
Ignore it.

836
00:40:55,180 --> 00:41:00,980
But when they heard a piano chord, their brain automatically tried to physically mirror the piano fingering,

837
00:41:01,120 --> 00:41:04,600
which crashed into the fingering they were consciously trying to perform.

838
00:41:04,600 --> 00:41:10,120
It proves that our bodies are hyper-tuned to simulate what we already know how to do physically.

839
00:41:10,660 --> 00:41:14,240
We all have that baseline cross-modal imitation we all sub-vocalize.

840
00:41:14,620 --> 00:41:19,640
But if you have specific physical expertise, your finger-to-finger mirroring is incredibly powerful.

841
00:41:19,860 --> 00:41:22,740
And sometimes, whether you are an expert or a novice,

842
00:41:22,880 --> 00:41:28,940
that primal urge to participate, to mirror the sound, is so powerful it overrides our logical brain entirely.

843
00:41:29,140 --> 00:41:30,880
It overrides social conditioning.

844
00:41:30,880 --> 00:41:35,420
Which brings us to one of the funniest and most touching stories in the entire book,

845
00:41:35,980 --> 00:41:37,700
the Thomas Kvostov concert.

846
00:41:37,920 --> 00:41:38,240
Yes.

847
00:41:38,900 --> 00:41:43,300
Thomas Kvostov is a highly respected classical bass baritone singer.

848
00:41:43,860 --> 00:41:44,840
This setting is important.

849
00:41:45,540 --> 00:41:50,400
A classical vocal recital is one of the most strictly regulated social environments on Earth.

850
00:41:50,420 --> 00:41:50,900
Oh, totally.

851
00:41:51,260 --> 00:41:56,140
You sit in velvet chairs, you wear nice clothes, you do not cough, you do not unwrap a lozenge,

852
00:41:56,140 --> 00:41:59,600
and you absolutely do not make a sound while the performer is singing.

853
00:41:59,600 --> 00:42:01,040
It is peak social etiquette.

854
00:42:01,760 --> 00:42:04,580
So Arnie Cox is sitting in the audience at this recital.

855
00:42:05,260 --> 00:42:07,860
Kvostov comes back out on stage for his final encore,

856
00:42:08,320 --> 00:42:12,680
and he starts singing the classic, deep, resonant song, Old Man River.

857
00:42:13,160 --> 00:42:18,140
A song with a massive, very specific, mimetic invitation for male voices.

858
00:42:18,280 --> 00:42:18,420
Right.

859
00:42:18,540 --> 00:42:22,240
So Cox is listening, and suddenly he keeps hearing this faint echo.

860
00:42:22,680 --> 00:42:26,140
He looks forward, and there is an elderly man sitting two rows ahead of him,

861
00:42:26,140 --> 00:42:30,620
and this man is just singing along out loud to Old Man River, in the middle of a classical recital.

862
00:42:30,940 --> 00:42:32,200
His wife is mortified.

863
00:42:32,360 --> 00:42:37,040
She keeps jabbing him in the ribs, shushing him, furiously whispering for him to be quiet.

864
00:42:37,780 --> 00:42:38,680
The old man stops.

865
00:42:39,340 --> 00:42:44,000
But then a few bars later, the melody swells, and he just starts singing again.

866
00:42:44,320 --> 00:42:45,520
He cannot stop himself.

867
00:42:45,740 --> 00:42:50,360
It is a beautiful, hilarious example of what the text calls the memetic imperative.

868
00:42:50,620 --> 00:42:51,580
The memetic imperative.

869
00:42:51,580 --> 00:42:52,660
I love that phrase.

870
00:42:52,760 --> 00:42:55,740
It sounds like a sci-fi concept, but it's just biology.

871
00:42:56,140 --> 00:42:59,700
If we connect this to the bigger picture, for that elderly man,

872
00:43:00,160 --> 00:43:03,760
the deep evolutionary social urge to participate in the music,

873
00:43:04,020 --> 00:43:07,660
to physically share in that emotional and vocal state with Kvostov,

874
00:43:07,880 --> 00:43:12,520
was stronger than a lifetime of societal conditioning about sitting quietly at a recital.

875
00:43:12,860 --> 00:43:13,000
Yeah.

876
00:43:13,060 --> 00:43:14,300
He was caught in a tug-of-war.

877
00:43:14,800 --> 00:43:17,900
He was forced to choose between strict, polite social etiquette

878
00:43:17,900 --> 00:43:21,400
and the overwhelming evolutionary reward of communal participation.

879
00:43:22,140 --> 00:43:24,040
And the memetic biology won.

880
00:43:24,240 --> 00:43:26,900
It totally reminds me of the Miles Davis anecdote in the text.

881
00:43:27,000 --> 00:43:29,600
It's the exact same phenomenon, just in a different genre.

882
00:43:29,740 --> 00:43:30,360
Ah, yes.

883
00:43:30,620 --> 00:43:33,380
The story about jazz saxophonist Bob Berg.

884
00:43:33,740 --> 00:43:33,960
Right.

885
00:43:34,160 --> 00:43:36,900
So Bob Berg is playing saxophone in Miles Davis' band.

886
00:43:37,680 --> 00:43:40,880
And during a live set, there is a specific section of a song

887
00:43:40,880 --> 00:43:43,940
where Berg is explicitly supposed to lay out.

888
00:43:44,520 --> 00:43:47,360
He's supposed to rest, hold his sax, and let the rhythm section play.

889
00:43:48,020 --> 00:43:51,120
But in the heat of the moment, the groove is so tight, he just plays anyway.

890
00:43:51,200 --> 00:43:52,240
He blows right over his rest.

891
00:43:53,200 --> 00:43:57,760
After the show, they are backstage, and Miles Davis, with his famous raspy voice,

892
00:43:58,140 --> 00:43:59,080
comes up to him and asks,

893
00:43:59,520 --> 00:44:01,080
Bob, why do you play in this spot?

894
00:44:01,360 --> 00:44:02,620
You're not supposed to play in this spot.

895
00:44:03,000 --> 00:44:04,120
And Berg defensively says,

896
00:44:04,680 --> 00:44:05,700
It sounded so good, Chief.

897
00:44:05,900 --> 00:44:06,620
I had to play it.

898
00:44:06,760 --> 00:44:09,420
To which Miles Davis delivers the ultimate rebuke.

899
00:44:09,480 --> 00:44:11,620
The reason it sounded so good is because you wasn't playing.

900
00:44:11,620 --> 00:44:15,340
Oh, a typical devastating Miles Davis burn.

901
00:44:16,000 --> 00:44:17,260
But look at Berg's defense.

902
00:44:17,820 --> 00:44:21,700
It is the exact same defense as the old band singing at the Kvostov Recital.

903
00:44:22,240 --> 00:44:24,040
It sounded so good I had to play it.

904
00:44:24,540 --> 00:44:27,100
The mimetic invitation of the rhythm section was so strong,

905
00:44:27,180 --> 00:44:30,200
his fingers and lungs literally could not resist joining in.

906
00:44:30,500 --> 00:44:33,600
And this highlights why live music is so fundamentally different

907
00:44:33,600 --> 00:44:36,120
and often more powerful than recorded music.

908
00:44:36,460 --> 00:44:39,460
In a live setting, the mimetic participation is amplified

909
00:44:39,460 --> 00:44:42,720
by the sheer danger and unpredictability of the event.

910
00:44:42,840 --> 00:44:43,560
What do you mean, danger?

911
00:44:43,560 --> 00:44:50,640
We are watching fragile human bodies attempt to perform incredibly complex physical tasks in real time.

912
00:44:51,120 --> 00:44:52,440
The singer might crack a note.

913
00:44:52,580 --> 00:44:53,960
The drummer might drop a stick.

914
00:44:54,220 --> 00:44:56,340
There is a real chance they might fail.

915
00:44:56,460 --> 00:44:56,940
Oh, I see.

916
00:44:57,020 --> 00:44:58,480
We are holding our breath with them.

917
00:44:58,580 --> 00:44:58,960
Exactly.

918
00:44:59,240 --> 00:45:01,780
When they succeed, when the tenor hits the high note,

919
00:45:01,780 --> 00:45:03,740
or the band nails the complex transition,

920
00:45:04,100 --> 00:45:07,820
we are vicariously achieving those musical goals right alongside them.

921
00:45:08,220 --> 00:45:11,200
The shared physical achievement is palpable in the room.

922
00:45:11,200 --> 00:45:14,280
So, up to this point, we have definitively established

923
00:45:14,280 --> 00:45:18,620
that listening to music is a deeply physical embodied experience.

924
00:45:19,240 --> 00:45:20,340
We are flexing our core.

925
00:45:20,540 --> 00:45:22,300
We are vibrating our vocal cords.

926
00:45:22,420 --> 00:45:23,940
We are firing our motor neurons.

927
00:45:24,100 --> 00:45:25,960
We are fighting the urge to sing out loud.

928
00:45:26,340 --> 00:45:27,380
We are moving our bodies.

929
00:45:27,660 --> 00:45:27,900
Yes.

930
00:45:28,180 --> 00:45:31,560
But how does all of this invisible internal physical activity

931
00:45:31,560 --> 00:45:36,060
dictate the actual words that come out of our mouths when we sit down to talk about music?

932
00:45:36,380 --> 00:45:39,620
This is where we cross from biology into linguistics.

933
00:45:39,620 --> 00:45:43,140
This brings us to the concept of the metaphors we listen by.

934
00:45:43,400 --> 00:45:45,080
Okay, let's unpack this language aspect.

935
00:45:45,240 --> 00:45:48,580
Because if you think about it, music is totally invisible.

936
00:45:49,140 --> 00:45:50,060
It is intangible.

937
00:45:50,260 --> 00:45:51,120
It is ephemeral.

938
00:45:51,240 --> 00:45:54,420
The second the note stops sounding, it ceases to exist.

939
00:45:54,540 --> 00:45:55,060
Exactly.

940
00:45:55,240 --> 00:45:56,580
You can't point to a C sharp.

941
00:45:57,040 --> 00:45:59,140
So, if we want to talk about it with another human being,

942
00:45:59,320 --> 00:46:02,120
we can't use literal physical descriptions.

943
00:46:02,460 --> 00:46:05,920
We have to use what linguists call conceptual metaphors.

944
00:46:06,240 --> 00:46:06,740
Exactly.

945
00:46:06,740 --> 00:46:11,800
The foundational theory here comes from cognitive linguists George Lakoff and Mark Johnson,

946
00:46:12,000 --> 00:46:14,360
who wrote a famous book called Metaphors We Live By.

947
00:46:14,880 --> 00:46:19,960
They proposed that human language and our entire conceptual system is fundamentally metaphorical.

948
00:46:20,480 --> 00:46:24,620
We only understand abstract, invisible things by mapping them onto concrete,

949
00:46:24,880 --> 00:46:27,040
physical experiences that we have had with our bodies.

950
00:46:27,300 --> 00:46:29,400
And they have a very specific formula for this mapping.

951
00:46:29,620 --> 00:46:31,200
Target domain is source domain.

952
00:46:31,200 --> 00:46:36,840
Yes, the target domain is the abstract, difficult concept we are trying to understand or explain.

953
00:46:37,340 --> 00:46:42,780
The source domain is the concrete, bodily, physical experience we use as a tool to explain it.

954
00:46:42,940 --> 00:46:44,100
Let me make sure I have this right.

955
00:46:44,260 --> 00:46:44,820
It's like Shakespeare.

956
00:46:45,500 --> 00:46:47,180
Romeo saying, Juliet is the sun.

957
00:46:47,760 --> 00:46:54,440
Juliet, or rather the abstract feeling of overwhelming, intoxicating teenage love that Romeo has for Juliet,

958
00:46:54,700 --> 00:46:55,900
is the target domain.

959
00:46:56,300 --> 00:46:57,800
The sun is the source domain.

960
00:46:57,980 --> 00:46:58,380
That's right.

961
00:46:58,380 --> 00:47:00,520
The sun is a concrete, physical object.

962
00:47:00,940 --> 00:47:01,760
It radiates heat.

963
00:47:02,000 --> 00:47:02,820
It provides light.

964
00:47:02,940 --> 00:47:04,040
It has immense gravity.

965
00:47:04,180 --> 00:47:04,760
It gives life.

966
00:47:05,340 --> 00:47:13,160
Romeo maps the literal warmth and gravity of the sun onto the abstract feeling of his love to explain his emotions to the audience.

967
00:47:13,560 --> 00:47:15,540
That is a perfect literary example.

968
00:47:15,540 --> 00:47:20,700
But Lakoff and Johnson argue we do this constantly in everyday language, not just in poetry.

969
00:47:21,100 --> 00:47:23,160
And we do it obsessively in music.

970
00:47:23,920 --> 00:47:28,240
The text points out how we take physical actions and nominalize them into musical objects.

971
00:47:28,440 --> 00:47:30,640
We turn physical verbs into musical nouns.

972
00:47:30,840 --> 00:47:31,440
Give me an example.

973
00:47:31,740 --> 00:47:33,180
Think about the terms we use for intervals.

974
00:47:33,600 --> 00:47:38,220
We call a small change in pitch musical step, and we call a large change in pitch a musical leap.

975
00:47:38,320 --> 00:47:38,520
Right.

976
00:47:38,880 --> 00:47:39,920
The melody takes a leap.

977
00:47:39,920 --> 00:47:41,920
But what is a leap, literally?

978
00:47:42,440 --> 00:47:45,420
A literal, physical leap is an exertion schema.

979
00:47:45,760 --> 00:47:55,460
It requires planning, a starting point, a sudden burst of physical effort in the legs, movement through three-dimensional space, and the shock of a landing.

980
00:47:55,460 --> 00:48:14,100
Because a musical interval, say, jumping from a low C to a high G requires a very similar feeling of sudden vocal exertion and transition in our throats when we subvocalize it, we map the physical action of jumping over a puddle onto the auditory experience of changing pitch.

981
00:48:14,300 --> 00:48:18,720
We call it a leap because it physically feels like a leap in our vocal cords.

982
00:48:18,800 --> 00:48:18,980
Right.

983
00:48:19,040 --> 00:48:20,400
And we do this with instruments, too.

984
00:48:20,460 --> 00:48:21,660
We don't just do it with notes.

985
00:48:21,740 --> 00:48:21,980
Right.

986
00:48:21,980 --> 00:48:25,920
The text has a whole section explaining how instrumental sounds are vocal sounds.

987
00:48:26,300 --> 00:48:31,880
We constantly aggressively filter the mechanical sounds of wood and brass through the metaphor of the human voice.

988
00:48:31,960 --> 00:48:34,500
Yes, look at the vocabulary of music criticism.

989
00:48:34,820 --> 00:48:40,940
We say an electric guitar is screaming, or a solo violin is weeping, or we praise a pianist for making the keys sing.

990
00:48:41,260 --> 00:48:49,000
We talk about a Bach fugue having four independent voices, even if all four lines are being played by one person on a completely mechanical pipe organ.

991
00:48:49,320 --> 00:48:50,020
Why do we do that?

992
00:48:50,020 --> 00:48:53,320
A saxophone is a piece of brass with a wooden reed.

993
00:48:53,400 --> 00:48:54,480
It doesn't have lungs.

994
00:48:54,800 --> 00:48:55,880
It cannot weep.

995
00:48:55,880 --> 00:49:03,140
Because the human voice was our primary, most fundamental evolutionary tool for acoustic emotional communication.

996
00:49:03,140 --> 00:49:13,920
Long before we invented flutes or drums, we screamed in terror, we wept in grief, we cooed in love, we map the emotional properties of the human voice onto mechanical instruments.

997
00:49:14,520 --> 00:49:30,920
We interpret a high, loud, distorted electric guitar solo as a scream because it triggers the exact same immodal and cross-modal mimetic responses in our nervous system as hearing a human being physically screaming in extreme agony or ecstasy.

998
00:49:30,920 --> 00:49:35,620
Okay, I hear you, but I have to push back here because I think the listener might be getting stuck on the same thing I am.

999
00:49:36,040 --> 00:49:42,020
I completely understand that a saxophone doesn't literally have vocal cords, so calling it sound of voice is clearly a poetic metaphor.

1000
00:49:42,200 --> 00:49:42,440
Sure.

1001
00:49:42,440 --> 00:49:48,660
But when I say a melody takes a leap, or more specifically, when I say a pitch is high or low, I don't feel like I'm using a metaphor.

1002
00:49:49,040 --> 00:49:50,200
That doesn't feel like poetry.

1003
00:49:51,000 --> 00:49:52,980
That is literally what the sheet music shows.

1004
00:49:53,100 --> 00:49:54,460
The notes go up and down the lines.

1005
00:49:54,820 --> 00:49:57,140
It feels like a literal, objective fact of music.

1006
00:49:57,140 --> 00:50:03,580
This is where Cox's work gets incredibly deep, and it challenges the very foundation of Western music.

1007
00:50:04,100 --> 00:50:12,780
The fact that calling a note high doesn't feel like a metaphor to you is actually proof of how deeply sedimented that metaphor is in our cognition.

1008
00:50:12,960 --> 00:50:13,860
Okay, explain that.

1009
00:50:13,980 --> 00:50:16,140
It is so ingrained we forget it's a metaphor.

1010
00:50:16,480 --> 00:50:21,940
We have to realize that the metaphor greater is higher is practically a universal human concept.

1011
00:50:22,140 --> 00:50:23,300
What do you mean greater is higher?

1012
00:50:23,300 --> 00:50:31,020
We universally map the physical dimension of vertical height onto abstract concepts of quantity, magnitude, or value.

1013
00:50:31,560 --> 00:50:33,260
Think about the phrases we use every day.

1014
00:50:33,360 --> 00:50:35,560
We say high prices, high quality, high stress.

1015
00:50:35,740 --> 00:50:35,840
Right.

1016
00:50:36,140 --> 00:50:39,620
Or, in the realm of emotion, we use the metaphor happy is up.

1017
00:50:39,700 --> 00:50:42,660
We say we are in high spirits, we are on top of the world.

1018
00:50:42,840 --> 00:50:46,460
Or conversely, we feel down in the dumps, we are feeling low.

1019
00:50:46,540 --> 00:50:47,240
Okay, but why?

1020
00:50:47,420 --> 00:50:48,500
Why is happy up?

1021
00:50:48,720 --> 00:50:50,840
Because of our physical bodies in the real world.

1022
00:50:50,840 --> 00:50:57,600
In childhood development, if you add more wooden blocks to a pile, the pile literally gets higher in space.

1023
00:50:58,080 --> 00:50:59,220
More equals higher.

1024
00:50:59,600 --> 00:51:08,560
If you stand up, proud, victorious, and happy, your posture straightens, and you are physically taller than if you were slumped over, defeated, and depressed.

1025
00:51:08,640 --> 00:51:09,000
Oh, wow.

1026
00:51:09,060 --> 00:51:09,900
That makes a lot of sense.

1027
00:51:10,100 --> 00:51:14,080
The physical correlation cements the conceptual metaphor in our developing brains.

1028
00:51:14,080 --> 00:51:20,760
More of something, or a more intense state of something, equates to being higher in physical space.

1029
00:51:20,840 --> 00:51:24,680
Okay, so we use height to describe intensity or quantity.

1030
00:51:25,440 --> 00:51:27,800
Which brings us to the ultimate musical illusion.

1031
00:51:28,640 --> 00:51:33,720
If high just means a greater quantity of something, what exactly is greater about a high note?

1032
00:51:33,720 --> 00:51:36,860
To answer that, we first have to shatter the illusion entirely.

1033
00:51:37,460 --> 00:51:43,020
We have to acknowledge that pitch height, the idea that notes go up and down in space, is not a universal human given.

1034
00:51:43,240 --> 00:51:44,900
It is a culturally constructed metaphor.

1035
00:51:45,160 --> 00:51:45,580
Wait, really?

1036
00:51:45,960 --> 00:51:47,400
Not everyone calls it high and low.

1037
00:51:47,780 --> 00:51:48,160
No.

1038
00:51:48,560 --> 00:51:56,120
The text points out that many other cultures throughout history have used completely different spatial or physical metaphors for pitch.

1039
00:51:56,120 --> 00:52:02,900
The Sia people, an indigenous group in South America, describe pitches as young and old.

1040
00:52:03,180 --> 00:52:04,440
Young for the squeaky notes.

1041
00:52:04,660 --> 00:52:05,820
Old for the deep notes.

1042
00:52:06,120 --> 00:52:06,600
Exactly.

1043
00:52:07,260 --> 00:52:10,340
The Balinese musical tradition uses small and large.

1044
00:52:10,740 --> 00:52:15,380
The ancient Greeks, who laid the foundation for much of our acoustic math, didn't use high and low.

1045
00:52:15,860 --> 00:52:20,380
They used the terms oxys and berries, which translate to sharp and heavy.

1046
00:52:20,640 --> 00:52:21,640
Sharp and heavy.

1047
00:52:21,760 --> 00:52:22,840
That is fascinating.

1048
00:52:22,840 --> 00:52:27,520
So the acoustic frequency of a sound wave doesn't inherently possess vertical height in the real world.

1049
00:52:28,300 --> 00:52:34,620
A 440 hertz sound wave and a note is physically hovering in the air two feet above a 220-yard sound wave.

1050
00:52:34,780 --> 00:52:36,900
They are just vibrating air at different speeds.

1051
00:52:37,020 --> 00:52:37,420
Exactly.

1052
00:52:37,560 --> 00:52:38,960
So why do we call it high and low?

1053
00:52:39,060 --> 00:52:42,940
Is it just because high frequencies have a greater number of vibrations per second?

1054
00:52:43,100 --> 00:52:43,360
Is it?

1055
00:52:43,500 --> 00:52:49,900
Well, human beings were singing high and low notes millennia before we had the technology to measure acoustic frequencies in hertz.

1056
00:52:49,900 --> 00:52:53,840
The spatial metaphor heavily predates the acoustic science.

1057
00:52:54,380 --> 00:53:01,620
The text argues that the concept of pitch height actually originates from one specific physical reality, human vocal exertion.

1058
00:53:01,680 --> 00:53:02,380
Vocal exertion.

1059
00:53:02,420 --> 00:53:04,180
How hard do we have to work to make the sound?

1060
00:53:04,320 --> 00:53:04,620
Yes.

1061
00:53:05,120 --> 00:53:06,960
Think about the physical mechanics of singing.

1062
00:53:07,580 --> 00:53:12,460
To sing a high note requires significantly greater physical exertion than singing a mid-range note.

1063
00:53:12,460 --> 00:53:23,260
It requires tighter vocal fold tension, vastly increased subglottal breath pressure from the lungs, and often a literal physical lifting of the chest, the chin, and the larynx.

1064
00:53:23,280 --> 00:53:24,800
Oh, I see where this is going.

1065
00:53:25,400 --> 00:53:33,320
And because of the memetic hypothesis, because we are constantly invisibly sub-vocalizing everything we hear when I listen to a high note played on a violin,

1066
00:53:34,040 --> 00:53:37,960
I am internally simulating that extreme physical effort in my own throat.

1067
00:53:37,960 --> 00:53:38,900
You've got it.

1068
00:53:39,000 --> 00:53:40,280
You simulate the effort.

1069
00:53:41,020 --> 00:53:46,360
And because your brain runs on the metaphor that greater physical effort equates to higher in space,

1070
00:53:46,780 --> 00:53:54,400
the note feels high, the pitch feels vertically elevated, because the muscular effort required to produce it is greater.

1071
00:53:54,740 --> 00:53:56,120
That is absolutely incredible.

1072
00:53:56,240 --> 00:54:00,520
We literally mistake our own muscular strain for spatial elevation.

1073
00:54:00,860 --> 00:54:06,220
And the text traces this linguistic habit all the way back to biblical origins, doesn't it?

1074
00:54:06,520 --> 00:54:06,960
It does.

1075
00:54:06,960 --> 00:54:14,820
It points to the ancient Hebrew words used for vocalizing in the Bible, words like nasa and rome, which literally translate to lift up.

1076
00:54:14,920 --> 00:54:16,180
They wouldn't say sing louder.

1077
00:54:16,300 --> 00:54:23,920
They would say lift up your voice, deeply tying the physical act of vocal exertion and emotional conveyance to upward vertical motion.

1078
00:54:24,280 --> 00:54:26,860
And we still use that exact same spatial phrasing today.

1079
00:54:27,040 --> 00:54:31,000
If someone is shouting in a restaurant, we don't tell them to reduce their subglottal breath pressure.

1080
00:54:31,100 --> 00:54:32,800
We say, hey, keep your voice down.

1081
00:54:32,800 --> 00:54:37,140
We are asking them to reduce their physical exertion, which we spatially metaphorizes down.

1082
00:54:37,760 --> 00:54:45,720
And this hidden biology of vocal exertion perfectly explains why climactic moments in music are so emotionally devastating to us as listeners.

1083
00:54:45,720 --> 00:54:50,440
Think of Puccini's famous opera aria, Nessun Dorn.

1084
00:54:50,480 --> 00:54:52,240
Oh, the legendary Pavarotti aria.

1085
00:54:52,360 --> 00:54:54,560
The one everyone knows, even if they don't know opera.

1086
00:54:54,780 --> 00:54:55,100
Yes.

1087
00:54:55,680 --> 00:55:01,060
At the very end of that aria, the tenor has to hit and hold a sustained high B.

1088
00:55:01,740 --> 00:55:03,760
It is a brutally difficult note.

1089
00:55:03,940 --> 00:55:07,840
It is hovering near the absolute anatomical limit of the human chest voice.

1090
00:55:07,840 --> 00:55:09,220
Yeah, you hear the strain.

1091
00:55:09,420 --> 00:55:17,440
The sheer, raw, physical effort required to generate that sound to maintain the breath pressure without your voice cracking or breaking is immense.

1092
00:55:17,520 --> 00:55:19,260
You can see the sweat on the singer's face.

1093
00:55:19,380 --> 00:55:23,400
And because of everything we've talked about, because of MMI and subvoculation and immodal limitation,

1094
00:55:24,020 --> 00:55:27,640
when I sit in the darkened auditorium and hear him hit that high B,

1095
00:55:28,240 --> 00:55:34,040
my brain, my throat, and my core muscles are silently simulating that exact same superhuman tension.

1096
00:55:34,660 --> 00:55:36,000
I am holding my breath with him.

1097
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:38,760
I am vicariously surviving that exertion.

1098
00:55:38,960 --> 00:55:39,180
You are.

1099
00:55:39,300 --> 00:55:44,680
You literally feel the triumph of the singer's physical exertion in the fibers of your own body.

1100
00:55:44,880 --> 00:55:48,420
The emotional climax of the story, the character's moment of triumph,

1101
00:55:48,540 --> 00:55:53,540
is perfectly, seamlessly married to the physical climax of the performer's body,

1102
00:55:53,700 --> 00:55:56,740
which is simultaneously mirrored in the listener's body.

1103
00:55:56,960 --> 00:55:59,280
It is a shared biological triumph.

1104
00:55:59,540 --> 00:56:05,140
So if I'm synthesizing all of this correctly, what does this mean for how we read music?

1105
00:56:05,140 --> 00:56:06,540
Think about sheet music.

1106
00:56:07,040 --> 00:56:11,940
The staff with the five lines, the little black dots with stems moving up and down the page.

1107
00:56:12,120 --> 00:56:15,320
I always thought that was a graph of sound waves, but it isn't, is it?

1108
00:56:15,480 --> 00:56:17,500
No, it's not a graph of sound waves in the air.

1109
00:56:17,780 --> 00:56:20,300
The sheet music is a map of the human body's effort.

1110
00:56:20,560 --> 00:56:21,980
It's a graph of muscular tension.

1111
00:56:22,520 --> 00:56:27,340
When the notes go up the page, it is a visual instruction to increase your bodily exertion.

1112
00:56:27,440 --> 00:56:31,300
That is a profoundly beautiful synthesis, and you are entirely correct.

1113
00:56:31,300 --> 00:56:35,440
The musical staff is a visual representation of an embodied metaphor.

1114
00:56:36,060 --> 00:56:40,100
We have built the entire towering architecture of Western music theory

1115
00:56:40,100 --> 00:56:44,440
upon the foundational reality of how our muscles tense and relax.

1116
00:56:44,620 --> 00:56:48,700
This completely changes everything about how I will ever listen to an album again.

1117
00:56:49,620 --> 00:56:52,160
Let's recap this incredible journey we have been on today,

1118
00:56:52,280 --> 00:56:55,040
because we covered a massive amount of ground.

1119
00:56:55,040 --> 00:57:00,200
We started with a simple, almost naive question from a blue-collar stove repairman

1120
00:57:00,200 --> 00:57:05,680
who just assumed, naturally, that studying music meant studying human feelings.

1121
00:57:05,940 --> 00:57:10,140
And after navigating through neurology, linguistics, and evolutionary biology,

1122
00:57:10,360 --> 00:57:11,900
we proved that he was absolutely right.

1123
00:57:12,240 --> 00:57:13,320
He was completely right.

1124
00:57:13,720 --> 00:57:17,180
We moved from that apartment to the nursery, looking at baby babble,

1125
00:57:17,620 --> 00:57:20,760
and how parents cooing is the birth of human empathy.

1126
00:57:20,760 --> 00:57:26,080
We talked about the visceral, uninhibited joy of playing air guitar and lip-syncing

1127
00:57:26,080 --> 00:57:28,660
to the Numa Numa song in a computer chair.

1128
00:57:28,740 --> 00:57:28,940
Yeah.

1129
00:57:29,320 --> 00:57:31,180
We unpacked the mirror neuron system,

1130
00:57:31,300 --> 00:57:34,720
proving that our tongues actually microscopically twitch when we hear speech,

1131
00:57:34,880 --> 00:57:38,100
and that our vocal cords silently stretch to the breaking point

1132
00:57:38,100 --> 00:57:41,540
when we hear a synthesizer climb into the stratosphere in a Nike commercial.

1133
00:57:41,820 --> 00:57:43,720
We explored the memetic invitation,

1134
00:57:43,980 --> 00:57:47,820
discovering how different songs physically ask us to do different things,

1135
00:57:47,820 --> 00:57:50,320
making us want to tap our feet, sing along,

1136
00:57:50,440 --> 00:57:54,620
or just clench our abdominal muscles in awe to a wall of Leggetti sound.

1137
00:57:55,180 --> 00:57:58,880
We talked about old men singing out loud at stuffy classical recitals

1138
00:57:58,880 --> 00:58:02,000
because the memetic urge is stronger than social politeness.

1139
00:58:02,520 --> 00:58:04,940
And finally, we arrived at this massive realization

1140
00:58:04,940 --> 00:58:10,220
that the very words we used to describe music steps, leaps, high, lows,

1141
00:58:10,340 --> 00:58:15,660
are all just metaphors mapping our bodily, physical actions onto invisible sounds.

1142
00:58:15,720 --> 00:58:16,060
Right.

1143
00:58:16,060 --> 00:58:21,100
When we listen to music, our bodies are silently, invisibly dancing, singing, and struggling along.

1144
00:58:21,500 --> 00:58:24,340
We don't just hear a symphony, we physically survive it.

1145
00:58:24,460 --> 00:58:27,820
Which, if we look at the ultimate conclusion of Arnie Cox's work,

1146
00:58:27,980 --> 00:58:33,160
leaves us with a rather profound and perhaps slightly unsettling implication to consider.

1147
00:58:33,460 --> 00:58:34,820
I am ready. Lay it on us.

1148
00:58:34,920 --> 00:58:36,740
If the memetic hypothesis is true,

1149
00:58:36,880 --> 00:58:43,080
if our bodies and our motor neurons are constantly subconsciously mimicking the acoustic sounds around us

1150
00:58:43,080 --> 00:58:46,760
to figure out what it's like to be that thing, making that sound,

1151
00:58:46,880 --> 00:58:48,820
what happens when you take off your headphones?

1152
00:58:49,120 --> 00:58:52,440
What happens when you step away from your carefully curated playlist?

1153
00:58:52,740 --> 00:58:53,300
Oh, wow.

1154
00:58:54,060 --> 00:58:55,500
I haven't even thought about the rest of the world.

1155
00:58:55,580 --> 00:58:59,600
We live in an incredibly violently noisy world.

1156
00:59:00,120 --> 00:59:05,480
If your nervous system and your muscles are always seeking to mirror the energy dynamics of your environment,

1157
00:59:05,480 --> 00:59:10,680
how is the ambient noise of your life secretly puppeteering your body right now?

1158
00:59:10,840 --> 00:59:11,560
Okay, like what?

1159
00:59:11,800 --> 00:59:12,380
Think about it.

1160
00:59:12,680 --> 00:59:15,620
The low, constant electrical hum of your refrigerator,

1161
00:59:16,060 --> 00:59:19,520
the sudden, violent screech of a subway car breaking on steel tracks,

1162
00:59:19,740 --> 00:59:24,760
the erratic, violent rhythm of a jackhammer tearing up the concrete outside your office window,

1163
00:59:24,760 --> 00:59:30,520
or, on the positive side, the gentle, sweeping rushing of wind through the trees in a park.

1164
00:59:30,740 --> 00:59:33,960
My body is trying to mimetically comprehend the jackhammer.

1165
00:59:34,080 --> 00:59:36,000
It's trying to simulate the mechanical violence.

1166
00:59:36,420 --> 00:59:36,720
Yes.

1167
00:59:37,340 --> 00:59:41,260
Your muscles are bracing your core, is reacting to the staccato bursts.

1168
00:59:41,620 --> 00:59:44,740
Your vocal cords are tightening at the screech of the subway.

1169
00:59:45,400 --> 00:59:47,600
These environmental sounds aren't just noise.

1170
00:59:47,760 --> 00:59:50,080
They are issuing constant mimetic invitations.

1171
00:59:50,080 --> 00:59:54,780
And they are shaping your physical tension, your stress levels, and your mood right now

1172
00:59:54,780 --> 00:59:57,380
without you ever consciously realizing it.

1173
00:59:57,700 --> 00:59:57,820
Wow.

1174
00:59:58,040 --> 01:00:01,840
So the question is, what are you mimetically participating in at this very second?

1175
01:00:02,060 --> 01:00:03,400
That is a staggering thought.

1176
01:00:03,560 --> 01:00:06,560
I am physically embodying the traffic outside my window.

1177
01:00:06,760 --> 01:00:09,240
It goes right back to where we started this entire deep dive.

1178
01:00:09,340 --> 01:00:09,460
Right.

1179
01:00:09,640 --> 01:00:13,100
We said at the beginning that you can look at an x-ray of a broken arm,

1180
01:00:13,180 --> 01:00:18,640
but you can't x-ray why a song makes you cry or why a city street makes you stressed.

1181
01:00:18,640 --> 01:00:21,660
Well, maybe we can't literally put it on an x-ray screen.

1182
01:00:21,840 --> 01:00:27,360
But thanks to Arnie Cox and the Manetic Hypothesis, we can finally feel the mechanism at work.

1183
01:00:27,540 --> 01:00:32,160
You can feel the tension in our throats, the rhythm in our gut, and the empathy in our muscles.

1184
01:00:32,520 --> 01:00:35,720
So to everyone listening to this right now, I have a challenge for you.

1185
01:00:35,780 --> 01:00:39,200
When this deep dive ends, go put on your absolute favorite song.

1186
01:00:39,540 --> 01:00:41,960
But this time, don't just passively listen to the melody.

1187
01:00:42,400 --> 01:00:45,660
Pay attention to what your gut, your chest, and your throat are doing.

1188
01:00:45,880 --> 01:00:48,540
Feel the invisible dance happening inside you.

1189
01:00:48,720 --> 01:00:50,380
Thanks for joining us on this deep dive.

1190
01:00:50,380 --> 01:00:50,400
Thanks for joining us on this deep dive.

